# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ripgrep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] See the guide's section on configuration files.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] ripgrep is a project whose contributors are volunteers.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] A release schedule adds undue stress to said volunteers.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Therefore, releases are made on a best effort basis and no dates **will ever be given**.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] An exception to this *can be* high impact bugs.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] If a ripgrep release contains a significant regression, then there will generally be a strong push to get a patch release out with a fix.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] If you installed ripgrep through a package manager on a Unix system, then it would have ideally been installed for you in the proper location.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] In which case, `man rg` should just work.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Note that the man page's documentation for options is equivalent to the output shown in `rg --help`.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] To see more condensed documentation (one line per flag), run `rg -h`.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] The man page is also included in all ripgrep binary releases.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] If you installed ripgrep through a package manager on a Unix system, then the shell completion files included in the release archive should have been installed for you automatically.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] If not, you can generate completions using ripgrep's command line interface.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Note though that while this approach is easier to setup, is generally slower than the previous method, and will add more time to loading your shell prompt.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] And then add `. _rg.ps1` to your PowerShell profile (note the leading period).
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] If the `_rg.ps1` file is not on your `PATH`, do `. /path/to/_rg.ps1` instead.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] By default, ripgrep uses parallelism to execute its search because this makes the search much faster on most modern systems.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] This in turn means that ripgrep has a non-deterministic aspect to it, since the interleaving of threads during the execution of the program is itself non-deterministic.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] This has the effect of printing results in a somewhat arbitrary order, and this order can change from run to run of ripgrep.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] The only way to make the order of results consistent is to ask ripgrep to sort the output.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Currently, this will disable all parallelism.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] (On smaller repositories, you might not notice much of a performance difference!) You can achieve this with the `--sort path` flag.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] See the guide's section on file encoding.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] ripgrep's `-z/--search-zip` flag will cause it to search compressed files automatically.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Currently, this supports gzip, bzip2, xz, lzma, lz4, Brotli and Zstd.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Each of these requires the corresponding `gzip`, `bzip2`, `xz`, `lz4`, `brotli` and `zstd` binaries to be installed on your system.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] ripgrep currently does not search archive formats, so `*.tar.gz` files, for example, are skipped.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] The `-U/--multiline` flag enables ripgrep to report results that span over multiple lines.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] ripgrep's default regex engine does not support lookaround or backreferences.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] This is primarily because the default regex engine is implemented using finite state machines in order to guarantee a linear worst case time complexity on all inputs.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Backreferences are not possible to implement in this paradigm, and lookaround appears difficult to do efficiently.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] However, ripgrep optionally supports using PCRE2 as the regex engine instead of the default one based on finite state machines.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] You can enable PCRE2 with the `-P/--pcre2` flag.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Most of the releases distributed by the ripgrep project here on GitHub will come bundled with PCRE2 enabled.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] If you installed ripgrep through a different means (like your system's package manager), then please reach out to the maintainer of that package to see whether it's possible to enable the PCRE2 feature.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] The `--color` flag accepts one of the following possible values: `never`, `auto`, `always` or `ansi`.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] The `auto` value is the default and will cause ripgrep to only enable colors when it is printing to a terminal.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] But if you pipe ripgrep to a file or some other process, then it will suppress colors.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] The `--colors` flag is a bit more complicated.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] A color is specified by either one of eight of English names, a single 256-bit number or an RGB triple (with over 16 million possible values, or "true color").
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] The color names are `red`, `blue`, `green`, `cyan`, `magenta`, `yellow`, `white` or `black`.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] A single 256-bit number is a value in the range 0-255 (inclusive).
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] It can either be in decimal format (e.g., `62`) or hexadecimal format (e.g., `0x3E`).
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] An RGB triple corresponds to three numbers (decimal or hexadecimal) separated by commas.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] As a special case, `--colors '{type}:none'` will clear all colors and styles associated with `{type}`, which lets you start with a clean slate (instead of building on top of ripgrep's default color settings).
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Colors are an ideal candidate to set in your configuration file.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] See the question on emulating The Silver Searcher's output style for an example specific to colors.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] First, see the previous question's answer on configuring colors.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Secondly, coloring on Windows is a bit complicated.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] If you're using a terminal like Cygwin, then it's likely true color support already works out of the box.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] However, if you are using a normal Windows console (`cmd` or `PowerShell`) and a version of Windows prior to 10, then there is no known way to get true color support.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] If you are on Windows 10 and using a Windows console, then true colors should work out of the box with one caveat: you might need to clear ripgrep's default color settings first.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] This is because ripgrep might set the default style for `match` to `bold`, and it seems like Windows 10's VT100 support doesn't permit bold and true color ANSI escapes to be used simultaneously.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] The work-around above will clear ripgrep's default styling, allowing you to craft it exactly as desired.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Type in `color` in cmd.exe (Command Prompt) and `echo -ne "\033[0m"` on Unix-like systems to restore your original foreground color.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] In PowerShell, you can add the following code to your profile which will restore the original foreground color when `Reset-ForegroundColor` is called.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Including the `Set-Alias` line will allow you to call it with simply `color`.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] PR #187 fixed this, and it was later deprecated in #281.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] If you're using cygwin on Windows and try to search for a pattern beginning with a `/`, then it's possible that cygwin is mangling that pattern without your knowledge.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] For example, if you tried running `rg /foo` in a cygwin shell on Windows, then cygwin might mistakenly perform path translation on `/foo`, which would result in `rg C:/msys64/foo` being searched instead.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Escape the leading slash with an additional slash. e.g., `rg //foo`.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Temporarily disable path translation by setting `MSYS_NO_PATHCONV=1`. e.g., `MSYS_NO_PATHCONV=1 rg /foo`.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] If you've given ripgrep a particularly large pattern (or a large number of smaller patterns), then it is possible that it will fail to compile because it hit a pre-set limit.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] (Note: `\pL{1000}` may look small, but `\pL` is the character class containing all Unicode letters, which is quite large.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Increasing the limit to 1GB does not necessarily mean that ripgrep will use that much memory.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] The limit just says that it's allowed to (approximately) use that much memory for constructing the regular expression.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] The `-f/--file` permits one to give a file to ripgrep which contains a pattern on each line. ripgrep will then report any line that matches any of the patterns.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] If this pattern file gets too big, then it is possible ripgrep will slow down dramatically.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] *Typically* this is because an internal cache is too small, and will cause ripgrep to spill over to a slower but more robust regular expression engine.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] If this is indeed the problem, then it is possible to increase this cache and regain speed.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] The cache can be controlled via the `--dfa-size-limit` flag.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] For example, using `--dfa-size-limit 1G` will set the cache size to 1GB.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Alternatively, add your color configuration to your ripgrep config file (which is activated by setting the `RIPGREP_CONFIG_PATH` environment variable to point to your config file).
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] When you use the `--pcre2` (`-P` for short) flag, ripgrep will use the PCRE2 regex engine instead of the default.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Both regex engines are quite fast, but PCRE2 provides a number of additional features such as look-around and backreferences that many enjoy using.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] This is largely because PCRE2 uses a backtracking implementation where as the default regex engine uses a finite automaton based implementation.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] The former provides the ability to add lots of bells and whistles over the latter, but the latter executes with worst case linear time complexity.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] With that out of the way, if you've used `-P` with ripgrep, you may have noticed that it can be slower.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] The reasons for why this is are quite complex, and they are complex because the optimizations that ripgrep uses to implement fast search are complex.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] The task ripgrep has before it is somewhat simple; all it needs to do is search a file for occurrences of some pattern and then print the lines containing those occurrences.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] The problem lies in what is considered a valid match and how exactly we read the bytes from a file.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] In terms of what is considered a valid match, remember that ripgrep will only report matches spanning a single line by default.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] The problem here is that some patterns can match across multiple lines, and ripgrep needs to prevent that from happening.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] For example, `foo\sbar` will match `foo\nbar`.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] The most obvious way to achieve this is to read the data from a file, and then apply the pattern search to that data for each line.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] The problem with this approach is that it can be quite slow; it would be much faster to let the pattern search across as much data as possible.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] It's faster because it gets rid of the overhead of finding the boundaries of every line, and also because it gets rid of the overhead of starting and stopping the pattern search for every single line.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] It turns out that we can use the faster approach by applying a very simple restriction to the pattern: *statically prevent* the pattern from matching through a `\n` character.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Namely, when given a pattern like `foo\sbar`, ripgrep will remove `\n` from the `\s` character class automatically.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] In some cases, a simple removal is not so easy.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] So what does this have to do with PCRE2?
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Well, ripgrep's default regex engine exposes APIs for doing syntactic analysis on the pattern in a way that makes it quite easy to strip `\n` from the pattern (or otherwise detect it and report an error if stripping isn't possible).
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] PCRE2 seemingly does not provide a similar API, so ripgrep does not do any stripping when PCRE2 is enabled.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] This forces ripgrep to use the "slow" search strategy of searching each line individually.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] OK, so if enabling PCRE2 slows down the default method of searching because it forces matches to be limited to a single line, then why is PCRE2 also sometimes slower when performing multiline searches?
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Well, that's because there are *multiple* reasons why using PCRE2 in ripgrep can be slower than the default regex engine.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] This time, blame PCRE2's Unicode support, which ripgrep enables by default.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] In particular, PCRE2 cannot simultaneously enable Unicode support and search arbitrary data.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] That is, when PCRE2's Unicode support is enabled, the data **must** be valid UTF-8 (to do otherwise is to invoke undefined behavior).
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] This is in contrast to ripgrep's default regex engine, which can enable Unicode support and still search arbitrary data. ripgrep's default regex engine simply won't match invalid UTF-8 for a pattern that can otherwise only match valid UTF-8.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] This author isn't familiar with its internals, so we can't comment on it here.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] The bottom line here is that we can't enable PCRE2's Unicode support without simultaneously incurring a performance penalty for ensuring that we are searching valid UTF-8.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] In particular, ripgrep will transcode the contents of each file to UTF-8 while replacing invalid UTF-8 data with the Unicode replacement codepoint. ripgrep then disables PCRE2's own internal UTF-8 checking, since we've guaranteed the data we hand it will be valid UTF-8.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] The reason why ripgrep takes this approach is because if we do hand PCRE2 invalid UTF-8, then it will report a match error if it comes across an invalid UTF-8 sequence.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] This is not good news for ripgrep, since it will stop it from searching the rest of the file, and will also print potentially undesirable error messages to users.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] All right, the above is a lot of information to swallow if you aren't already familiar with ripgrep internals.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Let's make this concrete with some examples.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] To search this data, we will use the pattern `^\w{42}$`, which contains exactly one hit in the file and has no literals.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Having no literals is important, because it ensures that the regex engine won't use literal optimizations to speed up the search.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] In other words, it lets us reason coherently about the actual task that the regex engine is performing.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Let's now walk through a few examples in light of the information above.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] In this particular example, both pattern searches are using a Unicode aware `\w` character class and both are counting lines in order to report line numbers.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] The key difference here is that the first search will not search line by line, but the second one will.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] The first says it is using the "fast line searcher" where as the latter says it is using the "slow line searcher." The latter also shows that we are decoding the contents of the file, which also impacts performance.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Interestingly, in this case, the pattern does not match a `\n` and the file we're searching is valid UTF-8, so neither the slow line-by-line search strategy nor the decoding are necessary.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] We could fix the former issue with better PCRE2 introspection APIs.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] We can actually fix the latter issue with ripgrep's `--no-encoding` flag, which prevents the automatic UTF-8 decoding, but will enable PCRE2's own UTF-8 validity checking.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] A possible reason why PCRE2's UTF-8 checking is slower is because it might not be better than the highly optimized UTF-8 checking routines found in the `encoding_rs` library, which is what ripgrep uses for UTF-8 decoding.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Moreover, my build of ripgrep enables `encoding_rs`'s SIMD optimizations, which may be in play here.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] All right, so at this point, you might think that we could remove the penalty for line-by-line searching by enabling multiline search.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] After all, our particular pattern can't match across multiple lines anyway, so we'll still get the results we want.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Search times remain the same with the default regex engine, but the PCRE2 search gets *slower*.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] The secrets can be revealed with the `--trace` flag once again.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] In the former case, ripgrep actually detects that the pattern can't match across multiple lines, and so will fall back to the "fast line search" strategy as with our search without `-U`.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] However, for PCRE2, things are much worse.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Namely, since Unicode mode is still enabled, ripgrep is still going to decode UTF-8 to ensure that it hands only valid UTF-8 to PCRE2.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Unfortunately, one key downside of multiline search is that ripgrep cannot do it incrementally.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Since matches can be arbitrarily long, ripgrep actually needs the entire file in memory at once.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Normally, we can use a memory map for this, but because we need to UTF-8 decode the file before searching it, ripgrep winds up reading the entire contents of the file on to the heap before executing a search.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] The file we're searching is *mostly* ASCII, so maybe we're OK with missing some data.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] For the most part, ripgrep's default regex engine performs about the same.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] PCRE2 does improve a little bit, and is now almost as fast as the default regex engine.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] If you look at the output of `--trace`, you'll see that ripgrep will no longer perform UTF-8 decoding, but it does still use the slow line-by-line searcher.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Ah, there's PCRE2's JIT shining! ripgrep's default regex engine once again remains about the same, but PCRE2 no longer needs to search line-by-line and it no longer needs to do any kind of UTF-8 checks.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] This allows the file to get memory mapped and passed right through PCRE2's JIT at impressive speeds.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] (As a brief and interesting historical note, the configuration of "memory map + multiline + no-Unicode" is exactly the configuration used by The Silver Searcher.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] In summary, if you want PCRE2 to go as fast as possible and you don't care about Unicode and you don't care about matches possibly spanning across multiple lines, then enable multiline mode with `-U` and disable PCRE2's Unicode support with the `--no-pcre2-unicode` flag.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Caveat emptor: This author is not a PCRE2 expert, so there may be APIs that can improve performance that the author missed.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Similarly, there may be alternative designs for a searching tool that are more amenable to how PCRE2 works.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] It's likely that you have a shell alias or even another tool called `rg` which is interfering with ripgrep.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Often you can find a need to make alias for commands you use a lot that set certain flags.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] But PowerShell function aliases do not behave like your typical linux shell alias.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] You always need to propagate arguments and `stdin` input.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Use below example as reference to how setup alias in PowerShell.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] This alias checks whether there is `stdin` input and propagates only if there is some lines.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Otherwise empty `$input` will make powershell to trigger `rg` to search empty `stdin`.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] To customize powershell on start-up, there is a special PowerShell script that has to be created.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] In order to find its location, type `$profile`.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] See Microsoft's documentation for more details.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Any PowerShell code in this file gets evaluated at the start of console.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] This way you can have own aliases to be created at start.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] When piping input into native executables in PowerShell, the encoding of the input is controlled by the `$OutputEncoding` variable.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] By default, this is set to US-ASCII, and any characters in the pipeline that don't have encodings in US-ASCII are converted to `?` (question mark) characters.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] To change this setting, set `$OutputEncoding` to a different encoding, as represented by a .NET encoding object.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] The value of this variable is reset when PowerShell restarts, so to make this change take effect every time PowerShell is started add a line setting the variable into your PowerShell profile.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] If you continue to have encoding problems, you can also force the encoding that the console will use for printing to UTF-8 with `[System.Console]::OutputEncoding = [System.Text.Encoding]::UTF8`.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] This will also reset when PowerShell is restarted, so you can add that line to your profile as well if you want to make the setting permanent.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Using ripgrep alone, you can't. ripgrep is a search tool that will never touch your files.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] However, the output of ripgrep can be piped to other tools that do modify files on disk.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] sed is one such tool that can modify files on disk. sed can take a filename and a substitution command to search and replace in the specified file.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] The output of this command is a list of filenames that contain a match for the `foo` pattern.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] This list can be piped into `xargs`, which will split the filenames from standard input into arguments for the command following xargs.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] You can use this combination to pipe a list of filenames into sed for replacement.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] will replace all instances of 'foo' with 'bar' in the files in which ripgrep finds the foo pattern.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] The `-i` flag to sed indicates that you are editing files in place, and `s/foo/bar/g` says that you are performing a **s**ubstitution of the pattern `foo` for `bar`, and that you are doing this substitution **g**lobally (all occurrences of the pattern in each file).
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Note: the above command assumes that you are using GNU sed.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] The `-i` flag in BSD sed requires a file extension to be given to make backups for all modified files.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Specifying the empty string prevents file backups from being made.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Finally, if any of your file paths contain whitespace in them, then you might need to delimit your file paths with a NUL terminator.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] To learn more about sed, see the sed manual here.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Additionally, Facebook has a tool called fastmod that uses some of the same libraries as ripgrep and might provide a more ergonomic search-and-replace experience.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] ripgrep is dual licensed under the Unlicense and MIT licenses.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Specifically, you may use ripgrep under the terms of either license.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] I, as ripgrep's author, would like as many people to use ripgrep as possible.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Since the Unlicense is not a proven or well known license, ripgrep is also offered under the MIT license, which is ubiquitous and accepted by almost everyone.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] More specifically, ripgrep and all its dependencies are compatible with this licensing choice.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] In particular, ripgrep's dependencies (direct and transitive) will always be limited to permissive licenses.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] That is, ripgrep will never depend on code that is not permissively licensed.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] This means rejecting any dependency that uses a copyleft license such as the GPL, LGPL, MPL or any of the Creative Commons ShareAlike licenses.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Whether the license is "weak" copyleft or not does not matter; ripgrep will **not** depend on it.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] If, upon hearing that "ripgrep can replace grep," you *actually* hear, "ripgrep can be used in every instance grep can be used, in exactly the same way, for the same use cases, with exactly the same bug-for-bug behavior," then no, ripgrep trivially *cannot* replace grep.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Moreover, ripgrep will *never* replace grep.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] If, upon hearing that "ripgrep can replace grep," you *actually* hear, "ripgrep can replace grep in some cases and not in other use cases," then yes, that is indeed true!
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Let's go over some of those use cases in favor of ripgrep.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] There may be other use cases not listed here that do apply to you.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Here are some cases where you might *not* want to use ripgrep.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] The same caveats for the previous section apply.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] When I first started writing ripgrep, I called it `rep`, intending it to be a shorter variant of `grep`.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Soon after, I renamed it to `xrep` since `rep` wasn't obvious enough of a name for my taste.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] And also because adding `x` to anything always makes it better, right?
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Before ripgrep's first public release, I decided that I didn't like `xrep`.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] I thought it was slightly awkward to type, and despite my previous praise of the letter `x`, I kind of thought it was pretty lame.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Being someone who really likes Rust, I wanted to call it "rustgrep" or maybe "rgrep" for short.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] But I thought that was just as lame, and maybe a little too in-your-face.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] But I wanted to continue using `r` so I could at least pretend Rust had something to do with it.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] I spent a couple of days trying to think of very short words that began with the letter `r` that were even somewhat related to the task of searching.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] I don't remember how it popped into my head, but "rip" came up as something that meant "fast," as in, "to rip through your text." The fact that RIP is also an initialism for "Rest in Peace" (as in, "ripgrep kills grep") never really dawned on me.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Perhaps the coincidence is too striking to believe that, but I didn't realize it until someone explicitly pointed it out to me after the initial public release.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] I admit that I found it mildly amusing, but if I had realized it myself before the public release, I probably would have pressed on and chose a different name.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Alas, renaming things after a release is hard, so I decided to mush on.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Given the fact that ripgrep never was, is or will be a 100% drop-in replacement for grep, ripgrep is neither actually a "grep killer" nor was it ever intended to be.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] It certainly does eat into some of its use cases, but that's nothing that other tools like ack or The Silver Searcher weren't already doing.
[src:ripgrep/blob-faq-md] Or if you'd prefer, donating to a charitable organization that you like would also be most welcome.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] This guide is intended to give an elementary description of ripgrep and an overview of its capabilities.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] This guide assumes that ripgrep is installed and that readers have passing familiarity with using command line tools.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] This also assumes a Unix-like system, although most commands are probably easily translatable to any command line shell environment.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] ripgrep is a command line tool that searches your files for patterns that you give it. ripgrep behaves as if reading each file line by line.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] If a line matches the pattern provided to ripgrep, then that line will be printed.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] If a line does not match the pattern, then the line is not printed.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] The best way to see how this works is with an example.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] To show an example, we need something to search.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Let's try searching ripgrep's source code.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] (**Note:** If you see an error message from ripgrep saying that it didn't search any files, then re-run ripgrep with the `--debug` flag.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] So what happened here? ripgrep read the contents of `README.md`, and for each line that contained `fast`, ripgrep printed it to your terminal. ripgrep also included the line number for each line by default.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] In this example, we searched for something called a "literal" string.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] This means that our pattern was just some normal text that we asked ripgrep to find.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] But ripgrep supports the ability to specify patterns via regular expressions.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] As an example, what if we wanted to find all lines have a word that contains `fast` followed by some number of other letters?
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] In this example, we used the pattern `fast\w+`.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] This pattern tells ripgrep to look for any lines containing the letters `fast` followed by *one or more* word-like characters.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Namely, `\w` matches characters that compose words (like `a` and `L` but unlike `.` and ).
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] The `+` after the `\w` means, "match the previous pattern one or more times." This means that the word `fast` won't match because there are no word characters following the final `t`.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] In this case, we used `fast\w*` for our pattern instead of `fast\w+`.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] The `*` means that it should match *zero* or more times.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] In this case, ripgrep will print the same lines as the pattern `fast`, but if your terminal supports colors, you'll notice that `faster` will be highlighted instead of just the `fast` prefix.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] In the previous section, we showed how to use ripgrep to search a single file.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] In this section, we'll show how to use ripgrep to search an entire directory of files.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] In fact, *recursively* searching your current working directory is the default mode of operation for ripgrep, which means doing this is very simple.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] (**Note:** We escape the `(` here because `(` has special significance inside regular expressions.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] In this example, we didn't specify a file at all.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Instead, ripgrep defaulted to searching your current directory in the absence of a path.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] In general, `rg foo` is equivalent to `rg foo ./`.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] This particular search showed us results in both the `src` and `termcolor` directories.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] The `src` directory is the core ripgrep code where as `termcolor` is a dependency of ripgrep (and is used by other tools).
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] What if we only wanted to search core ripgrep code?
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Here, ripgrep limited its search to the `src` directory.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Another way of doing this search would be to `cd` into the `src` directory and simply use `rg 'fn write\('` again.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] After recursive search, ripgrep's most important feature is what it *doesn't* search.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] `.ignore` globs, which take precedence over all gitignore globs when there's a conflict.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] This includes `.ignore` files in parent directories.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] `.rgignore` globs, which take precedence over all `.ignore` globs when there's a conflict.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] This includes `.rgignore` files in parent directories.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Hidden files and directories can be searched with the `--hidden` (`-.` for short) flag.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Binary files can be searched via the `--text` (`-a` for short) flag.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Binary files may emit control characters to your terminal, which might cause strange behavior.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] 4. ripgrep can follow symlinks with the `--follow` (`-L` for short) flag.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] As a special convenience, ripgrep also provides a flag called `--unrestricted` (`-u` for short).
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Repeated uses of this flag will cause ripgrep to disable more and more of its filtering.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] That is, `-u` will disable `.gitignore` handling, `-uu` will search hidden files and directories and `-uuu` will search binary files.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] This is useful when you're using ripgrep and you aren't sure whether its filtering is hiding results from you.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Tacking on a couple `-u` flags is a quick way to find out.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Sometimes you want to search files that are in your `.gitignore`, so it is possible to specify additional ignore rules or overrides in a `.ignore` (application agnostic) or `.rgignore` (ripgrep specific) file.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] This generally means that any `log` directory won't be tracked by `git`.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] However, perhaps it contains useful output that you'd like to include in your searches, but you still don't want to track it in `git`.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] ripgrep treats `.ignore` files with higher precedence than `.gitignore` files (and treats `.rgignore` files with higher precedence than `.ignore` files).
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] This means ripgrep will see the `!log/` whitelist rule first and search that directory.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Like `.gitignore`, a `.ignore` file can be placed in any directory.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Its rules will be processed with respect to the directory it resides in, just like `.gitignore`.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] To process `.gitignore` and `.ignore` files case insensitively, use the flag `--ignore-file-case-insensitive`.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] This is especially useful on case insensitive file systems like those on Windows and macOS.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Note though that this can come with a significant performance penalty, and is therefore disabled by default.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] For a more in depth description of how glob patterns in a `.gitignore` file are interpreted, please see `man gitignore`.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] In the previous section, we talked about ripgrep's filtering that it does by default.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] It is "automatic" because it reacts to your environment.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] That is, it uses already existing `.gitignore` files to produce more relevant search results.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] In addition to automatic filtering, ripgrep also provides more manual or ad hoc filtering.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] This comes in two varieties: additional glob patterns specified in your ripgrep commands and file type filtering.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] This section covers glob patterns while the next section covers file type filtering.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] In our ripgrep source code (see Basics for instructions on how to get a source archive to search), let's say we wanted to see which things depend on `lexopt`, our argument parser.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] But this shows us many things, and we're only interested in where we wrote `lexopt` as a dependency.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] The `-g '*.toml'` syntax says, "make sure every file searched matches this glob pattern." Note that we put `'*.toml'` in single quotes to prevent our shell from expanding the `*`.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] This will give you a lot of results again as above, but they won't include files ending with `.toml`.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Note that the use of a `!` here to mean "negation" is a bit non-standard, but it was chosen to be consistent with how globs in `.gitignore` files are written.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Globs are interpreted in exactly the same way as `.gitignore` patterns.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] That is, later globs will override earlier globs.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Interestingly, reversing the order of the globs in this case will match nothing, since the presence of at least one non-blacklist glob will institute a requirement that every file searched must match at least one glob.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] In this case, the blacklist glob takes precedence over the previous glob and prevents any file from being searched at all!
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Over time, you might notice that you use the same glob patterns over and over.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] The way the `--type` flag functions is simple.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] It acts as a name that is assigned to one or more globs that match the relevant files.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] This lets you write a single type that might encompass a broad range of file extensions.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] By default, ripgrep comes with a bunch of pre-defined types.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Generally, these types correspond to well known public formats.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] But you can define your own types as well.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] The above command defines a new type, `web`, corresponding to the glob `*.{html,css,js}`.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] It then applies the new filter with `-tweb` and searches for the pattern `title`.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Then you would see your `web` type show up in the list, even though it is not part of ripgrep's built-in types.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] It is important to stress here that the `--type-add` flag only applies to the current command.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] It does not add a new file type and save it somewhere in a persistent form.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] or add `--type-add=web:*.{html,css,js}` to your ripgrep configuration file.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] A special option supported by the `--type` flag is `all`.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] `--type all` looks for a match in any of the supported file types listed by `--type-list`, including those added on the command line using `--type-add`.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] It's equivalent to the command `rg --type agda --type asciidoc --type asm ...`, where `...` stands for a list of `--type` flags for the rest of the types in `--type-list`.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] As an example, let's suppose you have a shell script in your current directory, `my-shell-script`, which includes a shell library, `my-shell-library.bash`.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Both `rg --type sh` and `rg --type all` would only search for matches in `my-shell-library.bash`, not `my-shell-script`, because the globs matched by the `sh` file type don't include files without an extension.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] On the other hand, `rg --type-not all` would search `my-shell-script` but not `my-shell-library.bash`.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] ripgrep provides a limited ability to modify its output by replacing matched text with some other text.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] This is easiest to explain with an example.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Remember when we searched for the word `fast` in ripgrep's README?
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] What if we wanted to *replace* all occurrences of `fast` with `FAST`?
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] In essence, the `--replace` flag applies *only* to the matching portion of text in the output.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] If you instead wanted to replace an entire line of text, then you need to include the entire line in your match.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Finally, replacements can include capturing groups.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] For example, let's say we wanted to find all occurrences of `fast` followed by another word and join them together with a dash.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] The pattern we might use for that is `fast\s+(\w+)`, which matches `fast`, followed by any amount of whitespace, followed by any number of "word" characters.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] We put the `\w+` in a "capturing group" (indicated by parentheses) so that we can reference it later in our replacement string.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Our replacement string here, `fast-$1`, consists of `fast-` followed by the contents of the capturing group at index `1`.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] (Capturing groups actually start at index 0, but the `0`th capturing group always corresponds to the entire match.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Capturing groups can also be named, which is sometimes more convenient than using the indices.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] It is important to note that ripgrep **will never modify your files**.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] The `--replace` flag only controls ripgrep's output.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] It is possible that ripgrep's default options aren't suitable in every case.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] For that reason, and because shell aliases aren't always convenient, ripgrep supports configuration files.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Setting up a configuration file is simple. ripgrep will not look in any predetermined directory for a config file automatically.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Instead, you need to set the `RIPGREP_CONFIG_PATH` environment variable to the file path of your config file.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Once the environment variable is set, open the file and just type in the flags you want set automatically.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Lines starting with `#` (optionally preceded by any amount of whitespace) are ignored.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Each line is given to ripgrep as a single command line argument verbatim.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] When we use a flag that has a value, we either put the flag and the value on the same line but delimited by an `=` sign (e.g., `--max-columns=150`), or we put the flag and the value on two different lines.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] This is because ripgrep's argument parser knows to treat the single argument `--max-columns=150` as a flag with a value, but if we had written `--max-columns 150` in our configuration file, then ripgrep's argument parser wouldn't know what to do with it.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Putting the flag and value on different lines is exactly equivalent and is a matter of style.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Comments are encouraged so that you remember what the config is doing.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] So let's say you're using the above configuration file, but while you're at a terminal, you really want to be able to see lines longer than 150 columns.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Thankfully, all you need to do is pass `--max-columns 0` (or `-M0` for short) on the command line, which will override your configuration file's setting.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] This works because ripgrep's configuration file is *prepended* to the explicit arguments you give it on the command line.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Since flags given later override flags given earlier, everything works as expected.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] This works for most other flags as well, and each flag's documentation states which other flags override it.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] If you're confused about what configuration file ripgrep is reading arguments from, then running ripgrep with the `--debug` flag should help clarify things.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] The debug output should note what config file is being loaded and the arguments that have been read from the configuration.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] By default, ripgrep will not require its input be valid UTF-8.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] That is, ripgrep can and will search arbitrary bytes.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] The key here is that if you're searching content that isn't UTF-8, then the usefulness of your pattern will degrade.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] If you're searching bytes that aren't ASCII compatible, then it's likely the pattern won't find anything.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] With all that said, this mode of operation is important, because it lets you find ASCII or UTF-8 *within* files that are otherwise arbitrary bytes.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] As a special case, the `-E/--encoding` flag supports the value `none`, which will completely disable all encoding related logic, including BOM sniffing.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] When `-E/--encoding` is set to `none`, ripgrep will search the raw bytes of the underlying file with no transcoding step.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Of course, that's just an example meant to show how one can drop down into raw bytes.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Finally, it is possible to disable ripgrep's Unicode support from within the regular expression.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] For example, let's say you wanted `.` to match any byte rather than any Unicode codepoint.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] In addition to skipping hidden files and files in your `.gitignore` by default, ripgrep also attempts to skip binary files. ripgrep does this by default because binary files (like PDFs or images) are typically not things you want to search when searching for regex matches.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Moreover, if content in a binary file did match, then it's possible for undesirable binary data to be printed to your terminal and wreak havoc.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Unfortunately, unlike skipping hidden files and respecting your `.gitignore` rules, a file cannot as easily be classified as binary.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] In order to figure out whether a file is binary, the most effective heuristic that balances correctness with performance is to simply look for `NUL` bytes.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] At that point, the determination is simple: a file is considered "binary" if and only if it contains a `NUL` byte somewhere in its contents.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] The issue is that while most binary files will have a `NUL` byte toward the beginning of its contents, this is not necessarily true.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] The `NUL` byte might be the very last byte in a large file, but that file is still considered binary.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] While this leads to a fair amount of complexity inside ripgrep's implementation, it also results in some unintuitive user experiences.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Binary mode is similar to the default mode, except it will not always stop searching after it sees a `NUL` byte.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Namely, in this mode, ripgrep will continue searching a file that is known to be binary until the first of two conditions is met: 1) the end of the file has been reached or 2) a match is or has been seen.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] This means that in binary mode, if ripgrep reports no matches, then there are no matches in the file.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] When a match does occur, ripgrep prints a message similar to one it prints when in its default mode indicating that the search has stopped prematurely.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] This mode can be forcefully enabled for all files with the `--binary` flag.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] The purpose of binary mode is to provide a way to discover matches in all files, but to avoid having binary data dumped into your terminal.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Text mode completely disables all binary detection and searches all files as if they were text.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] This is useful when searching a file that is predominantly text but contains a `NUL` byte, or if you are specifically trying to search binary data.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] This mode can be enabled with the `-a/--text` flag.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Note that when using this mode on very large binary files, it is possible for ripgrep to use a lot of memory.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Unfortunately, there is one additional complexity in ripgrep that can make it difficult to reason about binary files.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] That is, the way binary detection works depends on the way that ripgrep searches your files.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] This means that whether a file is detected as binary or not can change based on the internal search strategy used by ripgrep.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] If you prefer to keep ripgrep's binary file detection consistent, then you can disable memory maps via the `--no-mmap` flag.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] In ripgrep, a preprocessor is any type of command that can be run to transform the input of every file before ripgrep searches it.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] This makes it possible to search virtually any kind of content that can be automatically converted to text without having to teach ripgrep how to read said content.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] PDFs are first and foremost meant to be displayed to users.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] But PDFs often have text streams in them that can be useful to search.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] In our case, we want to search Bruce Watson's excellent dissertation, Taxonomies and Toolkits of Regular Language Algorithms.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Surely, a dissertation on regular language algorithms would mention Commentz-Walter.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Indeed it does, but our search isn't picking it up because PDFs are a binary format, and the text shown in the PDF may not be encoded as simple contiguous UTF-8.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Namely, even passing the `-a/--text` flag to ripgrep will not make our search work.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] One way to fix this is to convert the PDF to plain text first.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] This won't work well for all PDFs, but does great in a lot of cases.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] But having to explicitly convert every file can be a pain, especially when you have a directory full of PDF files.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] Note that `preprocess` must be resolvable to a command that ripgrep can read.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] The simplest way to do this is to put your preprocessor command in a directory that is in your `PATH` (or equivalent), or otherwise use an absolute path.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] If you wind up needing to search a lot of PDFs, then ripgrep's parallelism can make the speed difference even greater.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] We can even extend our preprocessor to search other kinds of files.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] There is one more problem with the above approach: it requires running a preprocessor for every single file that ripgrep searches.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] If every file needs a preprocessor, then this is OK.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] But if most don't, then this can substantially slow down searches because of the overhead of launching new processors.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] You can avoid this by telling ripgrep to only invoke the preprocessor when the file path matches a glob.
[src:ripgrep/blob-guide-md] This section is intended to give you a sampling of some of the most important and frequently used options that will likely impact how you use ripgrep on a regular basis.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] ripgrep is a line-oriented search tool that recursively searches the current directory for a regex pattern.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] By default, ripgrep will respect gitignore rules and automatically skip hidden files/directories and binary files.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] (To disable all automatic filtering by default, use `rg -uuu`.) ripgrep has first class support on Windows, macOS and Linux, with binary downloads available for every release. ripgrep is similar to other popular search tools like The Silver Searcher, ack and grep.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] Dual-licensed under MIT or the UNLICENSE.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] Please see the CHANGELOG for a release history.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] This example searches the entire Linux kernel source tree (after running `make defconfig && make -j8`) for `[A-Z]+_SUSPEND`, where all matches must be words.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] Timings were collected on a system with an Intel i9-12900K 5.2 GHz.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] Please remember that a single benchmark is never enough!
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] See my blog post on ripgrep for a very detailed comparison with more benchmarks and analysis.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] Here's another benchmark on the same corpus as above that disregards gitignore files and searches with a whitelist instead.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] Now we'll move to searching on single large file.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] In the above benchmark, passing the `-n` flag (for showing line numbers) increases the times to `1.664s` for ripgrep and `9.484s` for GNU grep. ugrep times are unaffected by the presence or absence of `-n`.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] In other words, use ripgrep if you like speed, filtering by default, fewer bugs and Unicode support.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] Despite initially not wanting to add every feature under the sun to ripgrep, over time, ripgrep has grown support for most features found in other file searching tools.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] This includes searching for results spanning across multiple lines, and opt-in support for PCRE2, which provides look-around and backreference support.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] A large number of benchmarks with detailed analysis for each is available on my blog.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] Note that ripgrep has grown a few significant new features recently that are not yet present in Andy's table.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] This includes, but is not limited to, configuration files, passthru, support for searching compressed files, multiline search and opt-in fancy regex support via PCRE2.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] If you'd like to try ripgrep before installing, there's an unofficial playground and an interactive tutorial.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] If you have any questions about these, please open an issue in the tutorial repo.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] If you're a **Fedora** user, you can install ripgrep from official repositories.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] If you're an **openSUSE** user, ripgrep is included in **openSUSE Tumbleweed** and **openSUSE Leap** since 15.1.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] If you're a **Debian** user (or a user of a Debian derivative like **Ubuntu**), then ripgrep can be installed using a binary `.deb` file provided in each ripgrep release.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] If you run Debian stable, ripgrep is officially maintained by Debian, although its version may be older than the `deb` package available in the previous step.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] Various snaps for ripgrep on Ubuntu are also available, but none of them seem to work right and generate a number of very strange bug reports that I don't know how to fix and don't have the time to fix.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] If you're a **Rust programmer**, ripgrep can be installed with `cargo`.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] ripgrep is written in Rust, so you'll need to grab a Rust installation in order to compile it. ripgrep compiles with Rust 1.85.0 (stable) or newer.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] In general, ripgrep tracks the latest stable release of the Rust compiler.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] Enabling the PCRE2 feature works with a stable Rust compiler and will attempt to automatically find and link with your system's PCRE2 library via `pkg-config`.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] If one doesn't exist, then ripgrep will build PCRE2 from source using your system's C compiler and then statically link it into the final executable.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] Static linking can be forced even when there is an available PCRE2 system library by either building ripgrep with the MUSL target or by setting `PCRE2_SYS_STATIC=1`.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] ripgrep can be built with the MUSL target on Linux by first installing the MUSL library on your system (consult your friendly neighborhood package manager).
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] Applying the `--features` flag from above works as expected.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] If you want to build a static executable with MUSL and with PCRE2, then you will need to have `musl-gcc` installed, which might be in a separate package from the actual MUSL library, depending on your Linux distribution.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] ripgrep is relatively well-tested, including both unit tests and integration tests.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] For reporting a security vulnerability, please contact Andrew Gallant.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] The contact page has my email address and PGP public key if you wish to send an encrypted message.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] The following is a list of known translations of ripgrep's documentation.
[src:ripgrep/burntsushi-ripgrep] These are unofficially maintained and may not be up to date.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] A **command-line interface** (**CLI**), also known as a **command-line shell**, is a means of interacting with software via commands – each formatted as a line of text.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] The concept of interacting with a computer via text evolved over two decades, transitioning from physical hardware to sophisticated software.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Before the CLI, computers were programmed using physical switches or punched cards.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] The shift toward a "command" style interaction began with the use of Teleprinters (Teletypes).
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Early systems like the Whirlwind I (1951) at MIT began utilizing typewriter-like inputs for direct control, moving away from batch processing where you'd hand a stack of cards to an operator and wait hours for a result.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Devices like the Teletype Model 33, introduced in 1963, allowed operators to type a command and receive a printed response from the computer.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] The **command-line interpreter** emerged when computers became powerful enough to handle multiple users at once, known as Time-Sharing.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] The Compatible Time-Sharing System (CTSS), developed in 1961 at MIT, introduced the first true command-line interpreter.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] For the first time, a user could type a command like LOGIN or PRINT, and a dedicated program (the supervisor) would parse that text and execute the corresponding function.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] In 1964, Louis Pouzin introduced the software we now recognize as a "shell" for the Multics operating system, providing a programmable environment for executing scripts.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Many operating system and software development utilities provide CLI.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] A CLI enables automating programs since commands can be stored in a script file that can be used repeatedly.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] A script allows its contained commands to be executed as a group (as a single program).
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Alternatives to a CLI include a GUI (including the desktop metaphor such as Windows), text-based menuing (including DOS Shell and IBM AIX SMIT), and keyboard shortcuts.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Compared with a graphical user interface, a command-line interface requires fewer system resources to implement.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Since options to commands are given in a few characters in each command line, an experienced user often finds the options easier to access.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Automation of repetitive tasks is simplified by line editing and history mechanisms for storing frequently used sequences; this may extend to a scripting language that can take parameters and variable options.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] A command-line history can be kept, allowing review or repetition of commands.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] A command-line system may require paper or online manuals for the user's reference, although often a *help* option provides a concise review of the options of a command.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] The command-line environment may not provide graphical enhancements such as different fonts or extended edit windows found in a GUI.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] It may be difficult for a new user to become familiar with all the commands and options available, compared with the icons and drop-down menus of a graphical user interface, without reference to manuals.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Operating system (OS) command-line interfaces are usually distinct programs supplied with the operating system.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] A program that implements such a text interface is often called a command-line interpreter, command processor, or shell.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Under most operating systems, it is possible to replace the default shell program with alternatives; examples include 4DOS for DOS, 4OS2 for OS/2, and 4NT / Take Command for Windows.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] For example, the default Windows GUI is a shell GUI named EXPLORER.EXE, as defined in the SHELL=EXPLORER.EXE line in the WIN.INI configuration file.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] This program strictly speaking is a shell GUI and by extension a shell (strictly speaking, the Windows shell is shell32.dll not explorer.exe which is a shell GUI for shell32.dll), but it is not a CLI (command-line interpreter) nor a shell CLI (shell command-line interface).
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Application programs (as opposed to operating systems) may also have command-line interfaces.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Some applications support a CLI, presenting their own prompt to the user and accepting command lines.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Other programs support both a CLI and a GUI.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] In some cases, a GUI is simply a wrapper around a separate CLI executable file.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] In other cases, a program may provide a CLI as an optional alternative to its GUI.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs and GUIs often support different functionality.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] For example, all features of MATLAB, a numerical analysis computer program, are available via the CLI, whereas the MATLAB GUI exposes only a subset of features.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] In Colossal Cave Adventure from 1975, the user uses a CLI to enter one or two words to explore a cave system.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] The command-line interface evolved from a form of communication conducted by people over teleprinter (TTY) machines.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Sometimes these involved sending an order or a confirmation using telex.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Early computer systems often used a teleprinter to interact with an operator.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] The mechanical teleprinter was replaced by a "glass tty", a keyboard and screen emulating the teleprinter.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] "Smart" terminals permitted additional functions, such as cursor movement over the entire screen, or local editing of data on the terminal for transmission to the computer.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] As the microcomputer revolution replaced the traditional – minicomputer + terminals – time sharing architecture, hardware terminals were replaced by terminal emulators — PC software that interpreted terminal signals sent through the PC's serial ports.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] These were typically used to interface an organization's new PC's with their existing mini- or mainframe computers, or to connect PC to PC.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Some of these PCs were running Bulletin Board System software.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Early operating system CLIs were implemented as part of resident monitor programs, and could not easily be replaced.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] The first implementation of the shell as a replaceable component was part of the Multics time-sharing operating system.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] In 1964, MIT Computation Center staff member Louis Pouzin developed the RUNCOM tool for executing command scripts while allowing argument substitution.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Pouzin coined the term *shell* to describe the technique of using commands like a programming language, and wrote a paper about how to implement the idea in the Multics operating system.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Pouzin returned to his native France in 1965, and the first Multics shell was developed by Glenda Schroeder.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] The first Unix shell, the V6 shell, was developed by Ken Thompson in 1971 at Bell Labs and was modeled after Schroeder's Multics shell.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] The Bourne shell was introduced in 1977 as a replacement for the V6 shell.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Although it is used as an interactive command interpreter, it was also intended as a scripting language and contains most of the features that are commonly considered to produce structured programs.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] The Bourne shell led to the development of the KornShell (ksh), Almquist shell (ash), and the popular Bourne-again shell (or Bash).
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Early microcomputers themselves were based on a command-line interface such as CP/M, DOS or AppleSoft BASIC.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] During the 1980s and 1990s, the introduction of the Apple Macintosh and of Microsoft Windows on PCs saw the command line interface as the primary user interface replaced by the Graphical User Interface.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] The command line remained available as an alternative user interface, often used by system administrators and other advanced users for system administration, computer programming and batch processing.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] In November 2006, Microsoft released version 1.0 of Windows PowerShell (formerly codenamed *Monad*), which combined features of traditional Unix shells with their proprietary object-oriented .NET Framework.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] MinGW and Cygwin are open-source packages for Windows that offer a Unix-like CLI.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Microsoft provides MKS Inc.'s ksh implementation *MKS Korn shell* for Windows through their Services for UNIX add-on.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Since 2001, the Macintosh operating system macOS has been based on a Unix-like operating system called Darwin.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] On these computers, users can access a Unix-like command-line interface by running the terminal emulator program called Terminal, which is found in the Utilities sub-folder of the Applications folder, or by remotely logging into the machine using ssh.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Z shell is the default shell for macOS; Bash, tcsh, and the KornShell are also provided.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Before macOS Catalina, Bash was the default.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] A CLI is used whenever a large vocabulary of commands or queries, coupled with a wide (or arbitrary) range of options, can be entered more rapidly as text than with a pure GUI.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] This is typically the case with operating system command shells.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs are also used by systems with insufficient resources to support a graphical user interface.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Some computer language systems (such as Python, Forth, LISP, Rexx, and many dialects of BASIC) provide an interactive command-line mode to allow for rapid evaluation of code.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs are often used by programmers and system administrators, in engineering and scientific environments, and by technically advanced personal computer users.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs are also popular among people with visual disabilities since the commands and responses can be displayed using refreshable Braille displays.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] *External* commands run executables found in separate executable files.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] The command line interpreter searches for executable files with names matching the external command.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] In this format, the delimiters between command-line elements are whitespace characters and the end-of-line delimiter is the newline delimiter.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] This is a widely used (but not universal) convention.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] A command-line interface can generally be considered as consisting of syntax and semantics.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] The *syntax* is the grammar that all commands must follow.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] In the case of operating systems, DOS and Unix each define their own set of rules that all commands must follow.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] In the case of embedded systems, each vendor, such as Nortel, Juniper Networks or Cisco Systems, defines their own proprietary set of rules.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] These rules also dictate how a user navigates through the system of commands.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] The *semantics* define what sort of operations are possible, on what sort of data these operations can be performed, and how the grammar represents these operations and data—the symbolic meaning in the syntax.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Two different CLIs may agree on either syntax or semantics, but it is only when they agree on both that they can be considered sufficiently similar to allow users to use both CLIs without needing to learn anything, as well as to enable re-use of scripts.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] A simple CLI will display a prompt, accept a *command line* typed by the user terminated by the Enter key, then execute the specified command and provide textual display of results or error messages.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Advanced CLIs will validate, interpret and parameter-expand the command line before executing the specified command, and optionally capture or redirect its output.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Unlike a button or menu item in a GUI, a command line is typically self-documenting, stating exactly what the user wants done.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] In addition, command lines usually include many defaults that can be changed to customize the results.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] These advantages mean that a user must figure out a complex command or series of commands only once, because they can be saved, to be used again.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] where *doSomething* is, in effect, a verb, *how* an adverb (for example, should the command be executed *verbosely* or *quietly*) and *toFiles* an object or objects (typically one or more files) on which the command should act.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] The `>` in the third example is a redirection operator, telling the command-line interpreter to send the output of the command not to its own standard output (the screen) but to the named file.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Using `>>` will redirect the output and append it to the file.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Another redirection operator is the vertical bar (`|`), which creates a pipeline where the output of one command becomes the input to the next command.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] On some systems, such as Unix-like systems or Windows, one can modify the set of available commands by modifying which paths appear in the PATH environment variable or its equivalent.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] On Unix-like systems, the file containing the executable or script for a command also needs to be given execute permission.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] The directories in the path variable are searched in the order they are given.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] By re-ordering the path, one can run e.g.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] `\OS2\MDOS\E.EXE` instead of `\OS2\E.EXE`, when the default is the opposite.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Renaming of the executables also works: people often rename their favourite editor to EDIT, for example.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] The command line allows one to restrict available commands, such as access to advanced internal commands.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] The Windows CMD.EXE also supports restricting available commands.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Often, shareware programs will limit the range of commands, including printing a command 'your administrator has disabled running batch files' from the prompt.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Some CLIs, such as those in network routers, have a hierarchy of modes, with a different set of commands supported in each mode.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] The set of commands are grouped by association with security, system, interface, etc.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] In these systems the user might traverse through a series of sub-modes.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] For example, if the CLI had two modes called *interface* and *system*, the user might use the command *interface* to enter the interface mode.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] At this point, commands from the system mode may not be accessible until the user exits the interface mode and enters the system mode.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] In IBM's flagship MVS operating systems, the *Authorised Program Facility* (*APF*) allows certain *authorized programs* to run with enhanced privileges, analogous to UID(0) in Unix-like systems.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] TSO/E supports calling, e.g., authorized commands, but only for those commands, programs and services in an installation controlled list.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] A command prompt (or just *prompt*) is a sequence of (one or more) characters used in a command-line interface to indicate readiness to accept commands.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] It literally prompts the user to take action.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] A prompt usually ends with one of the characters `$`, `%`, `#`, `:`, `>` or `-` and often includes other information, such as the path of the current working directory and the hostname.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] On many Unix and derivative systems, the prompt commonly ends in `$` or `%` if the user is a normal user, but in `#` if the user is a superuser ("root" in Unix terminology).
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] On some systems, special tokens in the definition of the prompt can be used to cause external programs to be called by the command-line interpreter while displaying the prompt.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] In DOS' COMMAND.COM and in Windows NT's cmd.exe users can modify the prompt by issuing a `PROMPT` command or by directly changing the value of the corresponding `%PROMPT%` environment variable.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] The default of most modern systems, the `C:\>` style is obtained, for instance, with `PROMPT $P$G`.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] The default of older DOS systems, `C>` is obtained by just `PROMPT`, although on some systems this produces the newer `C:\>` style, unless used on floppy drives A: or B:; on those systems `PROMPT $N$G` can be used to override the automatic default and explicitly switch to the older style.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Many Unix systems feature the `$PS1` variable (Prompt String 1), although other variables also may affect the prompt (depending on the shell used).
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] In zsh the `$RPROMPT` variable controls an optional *prompt* on the right-hand side of the display.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] It is not a real prompt in that the location of text entry does not change.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] It is used to display information on the same line as the prompt, but right-justified.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] In RISC OS the command prompt is a `*` symbol, and thus (OS) CLI commands are often referred to as *star commands*.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] One can also access the same commands from other command lines (such as the BBC BASIC command line), by preceding the command with a `*`.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] In IBM's TSO, the command prompt is referred to as the READY prompt, after the word `READY` in the prompt.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Some shells, such as Bash, zsh, and PowerShell, allow the use of prompt systems that display a lot more information in the command prompt, like the type of remote connection, the state of machine sensors, or additional information about a version control system.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] They often use several ANSI colors, Unicode characters, and advanced shell features to set up a colorful display.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] A **command-line argument** or **parameter** is an item of information provided to a program when it is started.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] A program can have many command-line arguments that identify sources or destinations of information, or that alter the operation of the program.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] When a command processor is active a program is typically invoked by typing its name followed by command-line arguments (if any).
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] `file.s` is a command-line argument which tells the program rm to remove the file named `file.s`.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Some programming languages, such as C, C++ and Java, allow a program to interpret the command-line arguments by handling them as string parameters in the main function.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Other languages, such as Python, expose operating system specific API (functionality) through the `sys` module, and in particular `sys.argv` for *command-line arguments*.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] In Unix-like operating systems, a single hyphen used in place of a file name is a special value specifying that a program should handle data coming from the standard input or send data to the standard output.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] A **command-line option** or simply **option** (also known as a **flag** or **switch**) modifies the operation of a command; the effect is determined by the command's program.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Options follow the command name on the command line, separated by, e.g., commas, spaces.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Separators are not always required, such as `Dir/?` and `DIR /?` in DOS, which have the same effect of listing the DIR command's available options, whereas `dir --help` (in many versions of Unix) *does* require the option to be preceded by at least one space (and is case-sensitive).
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] The format of options varies widely between operating systems.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Command-line argument parsing is used to parse the arguments of a program, and such functionality is offered in various languages.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] For example, getopt() is in the C POSIX library for parsing arguments.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] In Multics, command-line options and subsystem keywords may be abbreviated.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] This idea appears to derive from the PL/I programming language, with its shortened keywords (e.g., STRG for STRINGRANGE and DCL for DECLARE).
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] For example, in the Multics *forum* subsystem, the *-long_subject* parameter can be abbreviated *-lgsj*.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] It is also common for Multics commands to be abbreviated, typically corresponding to the initial letters of the words that are strung together with underscores to form command names, such as the use of *did* for *delete_iacl_dir*.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] In some other systems abbreviations are automatic, such as permitting enough of the first characters of a command name to uniquely identify it (such as `SU` as an abbreviation for `SUPERUSER`) while others may have some specific abbreviations pre-programmed (e.g.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] `MD` for `MKDIR` in COMMAND.COM) or user-defined via batch scripts and aliases (e.g.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] On DOS, OS/2 and Windows, different programs called from their COMMAND.COM or CMD.EXE (or internal their commands) may use different syntax within the same operating system.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] In DOS, OS/2 and Windows, the forward slash (`/`) is most prevalent, although the hyphen-minus is also sometimes used.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] In some of these systems (MS-DOS/PC DOS 2.xx, DOS Plus 2.1, DR-DOS 7.02 and higher, PTS-DOS, Embedded DOS, FreeDOS and RxDOS), the setting can also be pre-configured by a SWITCHAR directive in CONFIG.SYS.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] General Software's Embedded DOS provides a SWITCH command for the same purpose, whereas 4DOS allows the setting to be changed via `SETDOS /W:n`.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Also, the current setting is reflected also in the built-in help screens.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Some versions of DR-DOS COMMAND.COM also support a PROMPT token `$/` to display the current setting.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] COMMAND.COM since DR-DOS 7.02 also provides a pseudo-environment variable named `%/%` to allow portable batchjobs to be written.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Several external DR-DOS commands additionally support an environment variable `%SWITCHAR%` to override the system setting.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] However, many programs are hardwired to use `/` only, rather than retrieving the switch setting before parsing command-line arguments.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] In Unix-like systems, the ASCII hyphen-minus begins options; the new (and GNU) convention is to use *two* hyphens then a word (e.g.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Two hyphen-minus characters without following letters (`--`) may indicate that the remaining arguments should not be treated as options, which is useful for example if a file name itself begins with a hyphen, or if further arguments are meant for an inner command (e.g., sudo).
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Double hyphen-minuses are also sometimes used to prefix *long options* where more descriptive option names are used.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] This is a common feature of GNU software.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] The *getopt* function and program, and the *getopts* command are usually used for parsing command-line options.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Unix command names, arguments and options are case-sensitive (except in a few examples, mainly where popular commands from other operating systems have been ported to Unix).
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Conversational Monitor System (CMS) uses a single left parenthesis to separate options at the end of the command from the other arguments.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] OS/360 operator commands use a comma separated list of positional and keyword parameters; only documented command and keyword abbreviations are valid.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Keyword values are separated from the keywords with equal signs.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] TSO commands use a space separated list of positional and keyword parameters; keywords may be truncated to any unique sub-string.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Only documented command abbreviations are valid.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] One of the criticisms of a CLI is the lack of cues to the user as to the available actions.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] In contrast, GUIs usually inform the user of available actions with menus, icons, or other visual cues.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] To overcome this limitation, many CLI programs display a usage message, typically when invoked with no arguments or one of `?`, `-?`, `-h`, `-H`, `/?`, `/h`, `/H`, `/Help`, `-help`, or `--help`.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] However, entering a program name without parameters in the hope that it will display usage help can be hazardous, as programs and scripts for which command line arguments are optional will execute without further notice.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Although desirable at least for the help parameter, programs may not support all option lead-in characters exemplified above.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Under DOS, where the default command-line option character can be changed from `/` to `-`, programs may query the SwitChar API in order to determine the current setting.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] So, if a program is not hardwired to support them all, a user may need to know the current setting even to be able to reliably request help.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] If the SwitChar has been changed to `-` and therefore the `/` character is accepted as an alternative path delimiter at the DOS command line, programs might misinterpret options like `/h` or `/H` as paths rather than help parameters.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] However, if given as the first or only parameter, most DOS programs will, by convention, accept it as a request for help regardless of the current SwitChar setting.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] In some cases, different levels of help can be selected for a program.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Some programs supporting this allow to give a verbosity level as an optional argument to the help parameter (as in `/H:1`, `/H:2`, etc.) or they give just a short help on help parameters with question mark and a longer help screen for the other help options.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Depending on the program, additional or more specific help on accepted parameters is sometimes available by either providing the parameter in question as an argument to the help parameter or vice versa (as in `/H:W` or in `/W:?` (assuming `/W` would be another parameter supported by the program)).
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] In a similar fashion to the help parameter, but much less common, some programs provide additional information about themselves (like mode, status, version, author, license or contact information) when invoked with an *about* parameter like `-!`, `/!`, `-about`, or `--about`.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Since the `?` and `!` characters typically also serve other purposes at the command line, they may not be available in all scenarios, therefore, they should not be the only options to access the corresponding help information.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] If more detailed help is necessary than provided by a program's built-in internal help, many systems support a dedicated external `help *command*`" command (or similar), which accepts a command name as calling parameter and will invoke an external help system.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] In addition to this, some newer versions of DR-DOS COMMAND.COM also accept a `?%` command to display a list of available built-in pseudo-environment variables.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Besides their purpose as quick help reference this can be used in batchjobs to query the facilities of the underlying command-line processor.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Notice that these characters have different meanings than when used directly in the shell.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Angle brackets may be omitted when confusing the parameter name with a literal string is not likely.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] In many areas of computing, but particularly in the command line, the space character can cause problems as it has two distinct and incompatible functions: as part of a command or parameter, or as a parameter or name separator.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Unix-based operating systems minimize the use of embedded spaces to minimize the need for quotes.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] In Microsoft Windows, one often has to use quotes because embedded spaces (such as in directory names) are common.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] The term **command-line interpreter** is applied to computer programs designed to interpret a sequence of lines of text which may be entered by a user, read from a file or another kind of data stream.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] The context of interpretation is usually one of a given operating system or programming language.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Command-line interpreters allow users to issue various commands in a very efficient (and often terse) way.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] This requires the user to know the names of the commands and their parameters, and the syntax of the language that is interpreted.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] The Unix `#!` mechanism and OS/2 EXTPROC command facilitate the passing of batch files to external processors.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] One can use these mechanisms to write specific command processors for dedicated uses, and process external data files which reside in batch files.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Many graphical interfaces, such as the OS/2 Presentation Manager and early versions of Microsoft Windows use command lines to call helper programs to open documents and programs.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] The commands are stored in the graphical shell or in files like the registry or the OS/2 `OS2USER.INI` file.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] The earliest computers did not support interactive input/output devices, often relying on sense switches and lights to communicate with the computer operator.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] This was adequate for batch systems that ran one program at a time, often with the programmer acting as operator.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] This also had the advantage of low overhead, since lights and switches could be tested and set with one machine instruction.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Later a single system console was added to allow the operator to communicate with the system.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] From the 1960s onwards, user interaction with computers was primarily by means of command-line interfaces, initially on machines like the Teletype Model 33 ASR, but then on early CRT-based computer terminals such as the VT52.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] All of these devices were purely text based, with no ability to display graphics or pictures.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] For business application programs, text-based menus were used, but for more general interaction the command line was the interface.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Around 1964 Louis Pouzin introduced the concept and the name *shell* in Multics, building on earlier, simpler facilities in the Compatible Time-Sharing System (CTSS).
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] From the early 1970s the Unix operating system adapted the concept of a powerful command-line environment, and introduced the ability to *pipe* the output of one command in as input to another.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Unix also had the capability to save and re-run strings of commands as shell scripts which acted like custom commands.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] The command line was also the main interface for the early home computers such as the Commodore PET, Apple II and BBC Micro – almost always in the form of a BASIC interpreter.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] When more powerful business-oriented microcomputers arrived with CP/M and later DOS computers such as the IBM PC, the command line began to borrow some of the syntax and features of the Unix shells such as globbing and piping of output.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] The command line was first seriously challenged by the PARC GUI approach used in the 1983 Apple Lisa and the 1984 Apple Macintosh.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] A few computer users used GUIs such as GEOS and Windows 3.1 but the majority of IBM PC users did not replace their COMMAND.COM shell with a GUI until Windows 95 was released in 1995.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Most command-line interpreters support scripting, to various extents.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] They are, after all, interpreters of an interpreted programming language, albeit in many cases the language is unique to the particular command-line interpreter.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] They will interpret scripts, variously termed shell scripts or batch files, written in the language that they interpret.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Some command-line interpreters also incorporate the interpreter engines of other languages, such as REXX, in addition to their own, allowing the executing of scripts, in those languages, directly within the command-line interpreter itself.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] Conversely, scripting programming languages, in particular those with an eval function (such as REXX, Perl, Python, Ruby or Jython), can be used to implement command-line interpreters and filters.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] For a few operating systems, most notably DOS, such a command interpreter provides a more flexible command-line interface than the one supplied.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p01] In other cases, such a command interpreter can present a highly customised user interface employing the user interface and input/output facilities of the language.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p02] The command line provides an interface between programs as well as the user.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p02] In this sense, a command line is an alternative to a dialog box.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p02] Editors and databases present a command line, in which alternate command processors might run.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p02] On the other hand, one might have options on the command line, which opens a dialog box.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p02] The latest version of 'Take Command' has this feature.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p02] DBase used a dialog box to construct command lines, which could be further edited before use.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p02] Programs like BASIC, diskpart, Edlin, and QBASIC all provide command-line interfaces, some of which use the system shell.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p02] Basic is modeled on the default interface for 8-bit Intel computers.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p02] Calculators can be run as command-line or dialog interfaces.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p02] Emacs provides a command-line interface in the form of its minibuffer.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p02] Commands and arguments can be entered using Emacs standard text editing support, and output is displayed in another buffer.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p02] There are a number of text mode games, like *Adventure* or *King's Quest 1-3*, which relied on the user typing commands at the bottom of the screen.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p02] One controls the character by typing commands like 'get ring' or 'look'.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p02] The program returns a text which describes how the character sees it, or makes the action happen.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p02] The text adventure *The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy*, a piece of interactive fiction based on Douglas Adams's book of the same name, is a teletype-style command-line game.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p02] The most notable of these interfaces is the standard streams interface, which allows the output of one command to be passed to the input of another.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p02] Text files can serve either purpose as well.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p02] This provides the interfaces of piping, filters and redirection.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p02] Under Unix, devices are files too, so the normal type of file for the shell used for stdin, stdout and stderr is a tty device file.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p02] Another command-line interface allows a shell program to launch helper programs, either to launch documents or start a program.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p02] The command is processed internally by the shell, and then passed on to another program to launch the document.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p02] The graphical interface of Windows and OS/2 rely heavily on command lines passed through to other programs – console or graphical, which then usually process the command line without presenting a user-console.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p02] Programs like the OS/2 E editor and some other IBM editors, can process command lines normally meant for the shell, the output being placed directly in the document window.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p02] A web browser's URL input field can be used as a command line.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p02] It can be used to *launch* web apps, access browser configuration, as well as perform a search.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p02] Google, which has been called "the command line of the internet" will perform a domain-specific search when it detects search parameters in a known format.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p02] This functionality is present whether the search is triggered from a browser field or on Google's website.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p02] There are JavaScript libraries that help developers write command line applications for the browser as standalone Web apps or as part of bigger applications.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p02] An example of such a website is the CLI interface to DuckDuckGo.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p02] There are also web-based SSH applications that allow access to a server’s command-line interface from a browser.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p02] Many PC video games feature a command line interface often referred to as a console.
[src:ripgrep/command-line-interface-p02] It is typically used by the game developers during development and by mod developers for debugging purposes as well as for cheating or skipping parts of the game.
[src:ripgrep/grep] Before it was named, grep was a private utility written by Ken Thompson to search files for certain patterns.
[src:ripgrep/grep] Doug McIlroy, unaware of its existence, asked Thompson to write such a program.
[src:ripgrep/grep] Responding that he would think about such a utility overnight, Thompson actually corrected bugs and made improvements for about an hour on his own program called `s` (short for "search").
[src:ripgrep/grep] The next day he presented the program to McIlroy, who said it was exactly what he wanted.
[src:ripgrep/grep] Thompson's account may explain the belief that grep was written overnight.
[src:ripgrep/grep] Thompson wrote the first version in PDP-11 assembly language to help Lee E.
[src:ripgrep/grep] McMahon analyze the text of *The Federalist Papers* to determine authorship of the individual papers.
[src:ripgrep/grep] He chose the name because in ed, the command `g/*re*/p`, where the *`re`* is the **r**egular **e**xpression to match, would print all lines featuring a specified pattern match. grep was first included in Version 4 Unix.
[src:ripgrep/grep] Stating that it is "generally cited as *the* prototypical software tool", McIlroy credited grep with "irrevocably ingraining" Thompson's tools philosophy in Unix.
[src:ripgrep/grep] A variety of grep implementations are available in many operating systems and software development environments.
[src:ripgrep/grep] Early variants included `egrep` and `fgrep`, introduced in Version 7 Unix.
[src:ripgrep/grep] The `egrep` variant supports an extended regular expression syntax added by Alfred Aho after Ken Thompson's original regular expression implementation.
[src:ripgrep/grep] The `fgrep` variant searches for any of a list of *fixed* strings using the Aho–Corasick string matching algorithm.
[src:ripgrep/grep] Binaries of these variants exist in modern systems, usually linking to grep or calling grep as a shell script with the appropriate flag added, e.g.
[src:ripgrep/grep] Commands `egrep` and `fgrep`, while commonly deployed on POSIX systems, to the point the POSIX specification mentions their widespread existence, are actually not part of POSIX.
[src:ripgrep/grep] Other commands contain the word "grep" to indicate they are search tools, typically ones that rely on regular expression matches.
[src:ripgrep/grep] The `pgrep` utility, for instance, displays the processes whose names match a given regular expression.
[src:ripgrep/grep] In the Perl programming language, `grep` is a built-in function that finds elements in a list that satisfy a certain property.
[src:ripgrep/grep] This higher-order function is typically named `filter` or `where` in other languages.
[src:ripgrep/grep] The `pcregrep` command is an implementation of grep that uses Perl regular expression syntax.
[src:ripgrep/grep] Similar functionality can be invoked in the GNU version of grep with the `-P` flag.
[src:ripgrep/grep] Ports of grep (within Cygwin and GnuWin32, for example) also run under Microsoft Windows.
[src:ripgrep/grep] Some versions of Windows feature the similar `qgrep` or `findstr` command.
[src:ripgrep/grep] A grep command is also part of ASCII's *MSX-DOS2 Tools* for MSX-DOS version 2.
[src:ripgrep/grep] The `grep`, `egrep`, and `fgrep` commands have also been ported to the IBM i operating system.
[src:ripgrep/grep] The software Adobe InDesign has functions GREP (since CS3 version (2007)), in the *find/change* dialog box "GREP" tab, and introduced with InDesign CS4 in *paragraph styles* "GREP styles".
[src:ripgrep/grep] This following invocation finds `netmasks` in file `myfile`, but also any other word that can be derived from it, given no more than two substitutions.
[src:ripgrep/grep] This example generates a list of matches with the closest, that is those with the fewest, substitutions listed first.
[src:ripgrep/grep] In December 2003, the *Oxford English Dictionary Online* added "grep" as both a noun and a verb.
[src:ripgrep/grep] A common verb usage is the phrase "You can't grep dead trees"—meaning one can more easily search through digital media, using tools such as grep, than one could with a hard copy (i.e. one made from "dead trees", which in this context is a dysphemism for paper).
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] ripgrep (rg) recursively searches the current directory for a regex pattern.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] By default, ripgrep will respect your **.gitignore** and automatically skip hidden files/directories and binary files.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] ripgrep's default regex engine uses finite automata and guarantees linear time searching.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Because of this, features like backreferences and arbitrary look-around are not supported.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] However, if ripgrep is built with PCRE2, then the **-P/--pcre2** flag can be used to enable backreferences and look-around.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Set **RIPGREP_CONFIG_PATH** to a configuration file.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] The file can specify one shell argument per line.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] For more details, see **CONFIGURATION** **FILES** below.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] ripgrep will automatically detect if stdin is a readable file and search stdin for a regex pattern, e.g.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] In some environments, stdin may exist when it shouldn't.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] To turn off stdin detection, one can explicitly specify the directory to search, e.g.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Like other tools such as **ls**, ripgrep will alter its output depending on whether stdout is connected to a tty.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] By default, when printing a tty, ripgrep will enable colors, line numbers and a heading format that lists each matching file path once instead of once per matching line.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Tip: to disable all smart filtering and make ripgrep behave a bit more like classical grep, use **rg -uuu**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] To a first approximation, ripgrep uses Perl-like regexes without look-around or backreferences.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This makes them very similar to the "extended" (ERE) regular expressions supported by *egrep*, but with a few additional features like Unicode character classes.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] If you're using ripgrep with the **-P/--pcre2** flag, then please consult https://www.pcre.org or the PCRE2 man pages for documentation on the supported syntax.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] A regular expression used for searching.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] File paths specified explicitly on the command line override glob and ignore rules.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This section documents all flags that ripgrep accepts.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Flags are grouped into categories below according to their function.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Note that many options can be turned on and off.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] In some cases, those flags are not listed explicitly below.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] For example, the **--column** flag (listed below) enables column numbers in ripgrep's output, but the **--no-column** flag (not listed below) disables them.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] For example, the **--no-ignore** flag (listed below) disables ripgrep's **gitignore** logic, but the **--ignore** flag (not listed below) enables it.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] These flags are useful for overriding a ripgrep configuration file (or alias) on the command line.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Each flag's documentation notes whether an inverted flag exists.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] In all cases, the flag specified last takes precedence.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Lines matching at least one of the provided patterns are printed.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag can also be used when searching for patterns that start with a dash.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] You can also use the special **--** delimiter to indicate that no more flags will be provided.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] When **-f/--file** or **-e/--regexp** is used, then ripgrep treats all positional arguments as files or directories to search.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Search for patterns from the given file, with one pattern per line.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] flag, then all patterns provided are searched.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Empty pattern lines will match all input lines, and the newline is not counted as part of the pattern.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] A line is printed if and only if it matches at least one of the patterns.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] When *PATTERNFILE* is **-**, then **stdin** will be read for the patterns.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] When this flag is set, ripgrep will unconditionally spawn a process for every file that is searched.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Therefore, this can incur an unnecessarily large performance penalty if you don't otherwise need the flexibility offered by this flag.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] flag to limit which files a preprocessor is run with.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] A preprocessor is not run when ripgrep is searching stdin.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] When searching over sets of files that may require one of several preprocessors, *COMMAND* should be a wrapper program which first classifies *PATH* based on magic numbers/content or based on the *PATH* name and then dispatches to an appropriate preprocessor.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Each *COMMAND* also has its standard input connected to *PATH* for convenience.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] The above script uses **pdftotext** to convert a PDF file to plain text.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] For all other files, the script uses the **file** utility to sniff the type of the file based on its contents.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] If it is a compressed file in the Zstandard format, then **pzstd** is used to decompress the contents to stdout.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This overrides the **-z/--search-zip** flag.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Any non-matching files will be searched without using the preprocessor command.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag is useful when searching many files with the **--pre** flag.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Namely, it provides the ability to avoid process overhead for files that don't need preprocessing.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] then it is possible to use **--pre** *pre-pdftotext* **--pre-glob** '**.pdf*' to make it so ripgrep only executes the *pre-pdftotext* command on files with a *.pdf* extension.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Multiple **--pre-glob** flags may be used.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Globbing rules match **gitignore** globs.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Precede a glob with a **!** to exclude it.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag has no effect if the **--pre** flag is not used.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag instructs ripgrep to search in compressed files.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Currently gzip, bzip2, xz, LZ4, LZMA, Brotli and Zstd files are supported.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] If the required binaries are not found, then ripgrep will not emit an error messages by default.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Note that this flag does not make ripgrep search archive formats as directory trees.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] It only makes ripgrep detect compressed files and then decompress them before searching their contents as it would any other file.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag can be disabled with **--no-search-zip**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This is a global option that applies to all patterns given to ripgrep.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Individual patterns can still be matched case insensitively by using inline regex flags.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] For example, **(?i)abc** will match **abc** case insensitively even when this flag is used.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag overrides the **-i/--ignore-case** and **-S/--smart-case** flags.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Principally, this permits the line anchor assertions **^** and **$** in regex patterns to treat CRLF, CR or LF as line terminators instead of just LF.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Note that they will never match between a CR and a LF.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] CRLF is treated as one single line terminator.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] When using the default regex engine, CRLF support can also be enabled inside the pattern with the **R** flag.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] For example, **(?R:$)** will match just before either CR or LF, but never between CR and LF.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag can be disabled with **--no-crlf**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] The default limit is something generous for any single pattern or for many smallish patterns.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This should only be changed on very large regex inputs where the (slower) fallback regex engine may otherwise be used if the limit is reached.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] The input format accepts suffixes of **K**, **M** or **G** which correspond to kilobytes, megabytes and gigabytes, respectively.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] If no suffix is provided the input is treated as bytes.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Specify the text encoding that ripgrep will use on all files searched.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] , which will cause ripgrep to do a best effort automatic detection of encoding on a per-file basis.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Automatic detection in this case only applies to files that begin with a UTF-8 or UTF-16 byte-order mark (BOM).
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] No other automatic detection is performed.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] which will then completely disable BOM sniffing and always result in searching the raw bytes, including a BOM if it's present, regardless of its encoding.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Other supported values can be found in the list of labels here: https://encoding.spec.whatwg.org/#concept-encoding-get.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] For more details on encoding and how ripgrep deals with it, see **GUIDE.md**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] The encoding detection that ripgrep uses can be reverted to its automatic mode via the **--no-encoding** flag.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Specify which regular expression engine to use.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] The default value is **default**, which is usually the fastest and should be good for most use cases.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] The **pcre2** engine is generally useful when you want to use features such as look-around or backreferences.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] **auto** will dynamically choose between supported regex engines depending on the features used in a pattern on a best effort basis.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Note that the **pcre2** engine is an optional ripgrep feature.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] If PCRE2 wasn't included in your build of ripgrep, then using this flag will result in ripgrep printing an error message and exiting.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This overrides previous uses of the **-P/--pcre2** and **--auto-hybrid-regex** flags.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Treat all patterns as literals instead of as regular expressions.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag can be disabled with **--no-fixed-strings**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] When this flag is provided, all patterns will be searched case insensitively.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] The case insensitivity rules used by ripgrep's default regex engine conform to Unicode's "simple" case folding rules.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Individual patterns can still be matched case sensitively by using inline regex flags.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] For example, **(?-i)abc** will match **abc** case sensitively even when this flag is used.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag overrides **-s/--case-sensitive** and **-S/--smart-case**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] That is, instead of printing lines that match, ripgrep will print lines that don't match.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Note that this only inverts line-by-line matching.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] For example, combining this flag with **-l/--files-with-matches** will emit files that contain any lines that do not match the patterns given.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] That's not the same as, for example, **--files-without-match**, which will emit files that do not contain any matching lines.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag can be disabled with **--no-invert-match**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] When enabled, ripgrep will only show matches surrounded by line boundaries.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] In other words, this only prints lines where the entire line participates in a match.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This overrides the **-w/--word-regexp** flag.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] When **-U/--multiline** is used, a single match that spans multiple lines is only counted once for the purposes of this limit.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Multiple matches in a single line are counted only once, as they would be in non-multiline mode.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] When combined with **-A/--after-context** or **-C/--context**, it's possible for more matches than the maximum to be printed if contextual lines contain a match.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Note that **0** is a legal value but not likely to be useful.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] When used, ripgrep won't search anything.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] When enabled, ripgrep will search using memory maps when possible.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This is enabled by default when ripgrep thinks it will be faster.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Memory map searching cannot be used in all circumstances.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] For example, when searching virtual files or streams likes **stdin**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] In such cases, memory maps will not be used even when this flag is enabled.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Note that ripgrep may abort unexpectedly when memory maps are used if it searches a file that is simultaneously truncated.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Users can opt out of this possibility by disabling memory maps.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag can be disabled with **--no-mmap**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag enable searching across multiple lines.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] When multiline mode is enabled, ripgrep will lift the restriction that a match cannot include a line terminator.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] For example, when multiline mode is not enabled (the default), then the regex **\p{any}** will match any Unicode codepoint other than **\n**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Similarly, the regex **\n** is explicitly forbidden, and if you try to use it, ripgrep will return an error.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] However, when multiline mode is enabled, **\p{any}** will match any Unicode codepoint, including **\n**, and regexes like **\n** are permitted.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] An important caveat is that multiline mode does not change the match semantics of **.**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Namely, in most regex matchers, a **.** will by default match any character other than **\n**, and this is true in ripgrep as well.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] In order to make **.** match **\n**, you must enable the "dot all" flag inside the regex.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] For example, both **(?s).** and **(?s:.)** have the same semantics, where **.** will match any character, including **\n**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Alternatively, the **--multiline-dotall** flag may be passed to make the "dot all" behavior the default.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag only applies when multiline search is enabled.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] There is no limit on the number of the lines that a single match can span.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This overrides the **--stop-on-nonmatch** flag.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag can be disabled with **--no-multiline**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag enables "dot all" mode in all regex patterns.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] to match line terminators when multiline searching is enabled.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Normally, a **.** will match any character except line terminators.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] While this behavior typically isn't relevant for line-oriented matching (since matches can span at most one line), this can be useful when searching with the **-U/--multiline** flag.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] By default, multiline mode runs without "dot all" mode enabled.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag is generally intended to be used in an alias or your ripgrep config file if you prefer "dot all" semantics by default.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Note that regardless of whether this flag is used, "dot all" semantics can still be controlled via inline flags in the regex pattern itself, e.g., **(?s:.)** always enables "dot all" whereas **(?-s:.)** always disables "dot all".
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Moreover, you can use character classes like **\p{any}** to match any Unicode codepoint regardless of whether "dot all" mode is enabled or not.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag can be disabled with **--no-multiline-dotall**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag disables Unicode mode for all patterns given to ripgrep.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] By default, ripgrep will enable "Unicode mode" in all of its regexes.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] In some cases it can be desirable to turn these things off.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] For example, Unicode mode can sometimes have a negative impact on performance, especially when things like **\w** are used frequently (including via bounded repetitions like **\w{100}**) when only their ASCII interpretation is needed.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag can be disabled with **--unicode**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This is useful when searching large binary files that would otherwise have very long lines if **\n** were used as the line terminator.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] In particular, ripgrep requires that, at a minimum, each line must fit into memory.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Using **NUL** instead can be a useful stopgap to keep memory requirements low and avoid OOM (out of memory) conditions.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This is also useful for processing NUL delimited data, such as that emitted when using ripgrep's **-0/--null** flag or **find**'s **--print0** flag.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] When this flag is present, ripgrep will use the PCRE2 regex engine instead of its default regex engine.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This is generally useful when you want to use features such as look-around or backreferences.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Using this flag is the same as passing **--engine=pcre2**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Users may instead elect to use **--engine=auto** to ask ripgrep to automatically select the right regex engine based on the patterns given.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag and the **--engine** flag override one another.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Note that PCRE2 is an optional ripgrep feature.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] PCRE2 may also have worse user experience in some cases, since it has fewer introspection APIs than ripgrep's default regex engine.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] For example, if you use a **\n** in a PCRE2 regex without the **-U/--multiline** flag, then ripgrep will silently fail to match anything instead of reporting an error immediately (like it does with the default regex engine).
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag can be disabled with **--no-pcre2**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] The size limit of the compiled regex, where the compiled regex generally corresponds to a single object in memory that can match all of the patterns provided to ripgrep.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] The default limit is generous enough that most reasonable patterns (or even a small number of them) should fit.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This useful to change when you explicitly want to let ripgrep spend potentially much more time and/or memory building a regex matcher.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag instructs ripgrep to searches case insensitively if the pattern is all lowercase.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Otherwise, ripgrep will search case sensitively.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This overrides the **-s/--case-sensitive** and **-i/--ignore-case** flags.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Enabling this option will cause ripgrep to stop reading a file once it encounters a non-matching line after it has encountered a matching line.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This is useful if it is expected that all matches in a given file will be on sequential lines, for example due to the lines being sorted.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This overrides the **-U/--multiline** flag.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag instructs ripgrep to search binary files as if they were text.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] When this flag is present, ripgrep's binary file detection is disabled.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This means that when a binary file is searched, its contents may be printed if there is a match.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This may cause escape codes to be printed that alter the behavior of your terminal.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] When binary file detection is enabled, it is imperfect.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] If a **NUL** byte is seen during search, then the file is considered binary and searching stops (unless this flag is present).
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Alternatively, if the **--binary** flag is used, then ripgrep will only quit when it sees a **NUL** byte after it sees a match (or searches the entire file).
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag overrides the **--binary** flag.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag can be disabled with **--no-text**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag sets the approximate number of threads to use.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] (which is the default) causes ripgrep to choose the thread count using heuristics.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] When enabled, ripgrep will only show matches surrounded by word boundaries.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This overrides the **-x/--line-regexp** flag.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] When this flag is used, ripgrep will dynamically choose between supported regex engines depending on the features used in a pattern.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] When ripgrep chooses a regex engine, it applies that choice for every regex provided to ripgrep (e.g., via multiple **-e/--regexp** or **-f/--file** flags).
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] As an example of how this flag might behave, ripgrep will attempt to use its default finite automata based regex engine whenever the pattern can be successfully compiled with that regex engine.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] If PCRE2 is enabled and if the pattern given could not be compiled with the default regex engine, then PCRE2 will be automatically used for searching.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] If PCRE2 isn't available, then this flag has no effect because there is only one regex engine to choose from.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] In the future, ripgrep may adjust its heuristics for how it decides which regex engine to use.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] In general, the heuristics will be limited to a static analysis of the patterns, and not to any specific runtime behavior observed while searching files.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] The primary downside of using this flag is that it may not always be obvious which regex engine ripgrep uses, and thus, the match semantics or performance profile of ripgrep may subtly and unexpectedly change.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] However, in many cases, all regex engines will agree on what constitutes a match and it can be nice to transparently support more advanced regex features like look-around and backreferences without explicitly needing to enable them.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag can be disabled with **--no-auto-hybrid-regex**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Note that Unicode mode is enabled by default.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag can be disabled with **--pcre2-unicode**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Enabling this flag will cause ripgrep to search binary files.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] By default, ripgrep attempts to automatically skip binary files in order to improve the relevance of results and make the search faster.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Binary files are heuristically detected based on whether they contain a **NUL** byte or not.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] By default (without this flag set), once a **NUL** byte is seen, ripgrep will stop searching the file.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Usually, **NUL** bytes occur in the beginning of most binary files.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] If a **NUL** byte occurs after a match, then ripgrep will not print the match, stop searching that file, and emit a warning that some matches are being suppressed.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] In contrast, when this flag is provided, ripgrep will continue searching a file even if a **NUL** byte is found.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] In particular, if a **NUL** byte is found then ripgrep will continue searching until either a match is found or the end of the file is reached, whichever comes sooner.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] If a match is found, then ripgrep will stop and print a warning saying that the search stopped prematurely.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] If you want ripgrep to search a file without any special **NUL** byte handling at all (and potentially print binary data to stdout), then you should use the **-a/--text** flag.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] The **--binary** flag is a flag for controlling ripgrep's automatic filtering mechanism.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] As such, it does not need to be used when searching a file explicitly or when searching stdin.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] That is, it is only applicable when recursively searching a directory.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] When the **-u/--unrestricted** flag is provided for a third time, then this flag is automatically enabled.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag overrides the **-a/--text** flag.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag can be disabled with **--no-binary**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag instructs ripgrep to follow symbolic links while traversing directories.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Note that ripgrep will check for symbolic link loops and report errors if it finds one. ripgrep will also report errors for broken links.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag can be disabled with **--no-follow**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Include or exclude files and directories for searching that match the given glob.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This always overrides any other ignore logic.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] If multiple globs match a file or directory, the glob given later in the command line takes precedence.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] As an extension, globs support specifying alternatives: **-g '***ab{c,d}****'** is equivalent to **-g***abc***-g***abd.* Empty alternatives like **-g '***ab{,c}***'** are not currently supported.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Note that this syntax extension is also currently enabled in **gitignore** files, even though this syntax isn't supported by git itself. ripgrep may disable this syntax extension in gitignore files, but it will always remain available via the **-g/--glob** flag.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] When this flag is set, every file and directory is applied to it to test for a match.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] For example, if you only want to search in a particular directory *foo*, then **-g***foo* is incorrect because *foo/bar* does not match the glob *foo*.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag can be disabled with **--no-glob-case-insensitive**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] By default, hidden files and directories are skipped.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Note that if a hidden file or a directory is whitelisted in an ignore file, then it will be searched even if this flag isn't provided.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Similarly if a hidden file or directory is given explicitly as an argument to ripgrep.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] A file or directory is considered hidden if its base name starts with a dot character (**.**).
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] On operating systems which support a "hidden" file attribute, like Windows, files with this attribute are also considered hidden.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Note that **-./--hidden** will include files and folders like **.git** regardless of **--no-ignore-vcs**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] To exclude such paths when using **-./--hidden**, you must explicitly ignore them using another flag or ignore file.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag can be disabled with **--no-hidden**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Globs used via this flag are matched case insensitively.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] are applied and are matched relative to the current working directory.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] That is, files specified via this flag have lower precedence than files automatically found in the directory tree.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Multiple additional ignore files can be specified by using this flag repeatedly.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] When specifying multiple ignore files, earlier files have lower precedence than later files.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] If you are looking for a way to include or exclude files and directories directly on the command line, then use **-g/--glob** instead.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Note that this comes with a performance penalty and is most useful on case insensitive file systems (such as Windows).
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag can be disabled with **--no-ignore-file-case-insensitive**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] only searches the explicitly given paths themselves.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] For example, **rg --max-depth 0***dir/* is a no-op because *dir/* will not be descended into.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] **rg --max-depth 1***dir/* will search only the direct children of *dir*.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] An alternative spelling for this flag is **--maxdepth**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This does not imply **--no-ignore-files**, since **--ignore-file** is specified explicitly as a command line argument.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] When given only once, the **-u/--unrestricted** flag is identical in behavior to this flag and can be considered an alias.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] However, subsequent **-u/--unrestricted** flags have additional effects.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag can be disabled with **--ignore**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This does not impact whether ripgrep will ignore files and directories whose names begin with a dot.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag also does not impact whether filter rules from **.gitignore** files are respected.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag can be disabled with **--ignore-dot**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Don't respect filter rules from files that are manually configured for the repository.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag can be disabled with **--ignore-exclude**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] flags, even ones that come after this flag, are ignored.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag can be disabled with **--ignore-files**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag can be disabled with **--ignore-global**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] When this flag is set, filter rules from ignore files found in parent directories are not respected.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] By default, ripgrep will ascend the parent directories of the current working directory to look for any applicable ignore files that should be applied.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] In some cases this may not be desirable.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag can be disabled with **--ignore-parent**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] 's ignore rules for automatic filtering.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Note that this flag does not directly affect the filtering of source control files or folders that start with a dot (**.**), like **.git**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] These are affected by **-./--hidden** and its related flags instead.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag implies **--no-ignore-parent** for source control ignore files as well.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag can be disabled with **--ignore-vcs**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] By default, ripgrep will only respect filter rules from source control ignore files when ripgrep detects that the search is executed inside a source control repository.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] For example, when a **.git** directory is observed.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag relaxes the default restriction.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] For example, it might be useful when the contents of a **git** repository are stored or copied somewhere, but where the repository state is absent.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag can be disabled with **--require-git**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] When enabled, ripgrep will not cross file system boundaries relative to where the search started from.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Note that this applies to each path argument given to ripgrep.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] ripgrep will search both */foo/bar* and */quux/baz* even if they are on different file systems, but will not cross a file system boundary when traversing each path's directory tree.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This is similar to **find**'s **-xdev** or **-mount** flag.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag can be disabled with **--no-one-file-system**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag supports the special value **all**, which will behave as if **-t/--type** was provided for every file type supported by ripgrep (including any custom file types).
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] The end result is that **--type=all** causes ripgrep to search in "whitelist" mode, where it will only search files it recognizes via its type definitions.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Note that this flag has lower precedence than both the **-g/--glob** flag and any rules found in ignore files.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] To see the list of available file types, use the **--type-list** flag.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag supports the special value **all**, which will behave as if **-T/--type-not** was provided for every file type supported by ripgrep (including any custom file types).
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] The end result is that **--type-not=all** causes ripgrep to search in "blacklist" mode, where it will only search files that are unrecognized by its type definitions.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag adds a new glob for a particular file type.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] is used, globs are added to any existing globs defined inside of ripgrep.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Note that this must be passed to every invocation of ripgrep.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] See **CONFIGURATION FILES** for a workaround.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag can also be used to include rules from other types with the special include directive.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] The include directive permits specifying one or more other type names (separated by a comma) that have been defined and its rules will automatically be imported into the type specified.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Note that type names must consist only of Unicode letters or numbers.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] , but globs can be added after this flag.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] This flag reduces the level of "smart" filtering.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Repeated uses (up to 3) reduces the filtering even more.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] When repeated three times, ripgrep will search every file in a directory tree.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] A single **-u/--unrestricted** flag is equivalent to **--no-ignore**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] The only filtering ripgrep still does when **-uuu** is given is to skip symbolic links and to avoid printing matches from binary files.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p01] Symbolic links can be followed via the **-L/--follow** flag, and binary files can be treated as text files via the **-a/--text** flag.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This overrides the **--passthru** flag and partially overrides the **-C/--context** flag.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] When enabled, ripgrep will use block buffering.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] That is, whenever a matching line is found, it will be written to an in-memory buffer and will not be written to stdout until the buffer reaches a certain size.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This is the default when ripgrep's stdout is redirected to a pipeline or a file.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] When ripgrep's stdout is connected to a tty, line buffering will be used by default.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Forcing block buffering can be useful when dumping a large amount of contents to a tty.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This overrides the **--line-buffered** flag.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag can be disabled with **--no-block-buffered**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Print the 0-based byte offset within the input file before each line of output.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] is specified, print the offset of the matched text itself.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] If ripgrep does transcoding, then the byte offset is in terms of the result of transcoding and not the original data.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This applies similarly to other transformations on the data, such as decompression or a **--pre** filter.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag can be disabled with **--no-byte-offset**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] , which means ripgrep will try to guess when to use colors.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] For example, if ripgrep is printing to a tty, then it will use colors, but if it is redirected to a file or a pipe, then it will suppress color output.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] ripgrep will suppress color output by default in some other circumstances as well.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Colors will always be used regardless of where output is sent.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Like 'always', but emits ANSI escapes (even in a Windows console).
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag also controls whether hyperlinks are emitted.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] For example, when a hyperlink format is specified, hyperlinks won't be used when color is suppressed.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag specifies color settings for use in the output.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag may be provided multiple times.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] *value* is either a color (for **fg** and **bg**) or a text style.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] A special format, **{***type***}:none**, will clear all color settings for *type*.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] The "highlight" color type is particularly useful for contrasting matching lines with surrounding context printed by the **-B/--before-context**, **-A/--after-context**, **-C/--context** or **--passthru** flags.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Extended colors can be used for *value* when the tty supports ANSI color sequences.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] *x* may be given as a normal decimal number or a hexadecimal number, which is prefixed by **0x**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Note that the **intense** and **nointense** styles will have no effect when used alongside these extended color codes.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This only shows the column numbers for the first match on each line.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This does not try to account for Unicode.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] When **-o/--only-matching** is used, then the column numbers written correspond to the start of each match.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag can be disabled with **--no-column**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] The **-A/--after-context** and **-B/--before-context** flags both partially override this flag, regardless of the order.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] The string used to separate non-contiguous context lines in the output.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] When the context separator is set to an empty string, then a line break is still inserted.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] To completely disable context separators, use the **--no-context-separator** flag.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This separator is only used when printing contextual lines.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] It is used to delimit file paths, line numbers, columns and the contextual line itself.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] The separator may be any number of bytes, including zero.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] The **-** character is the default value.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This separator is only used when printing matching lines.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] It is used to delimit file paths, line numbers, columns and the matching line itself.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] The **:** character is the default value.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag prints the file path above clusters of matches from each file instead of printing the file path as a prefix for each matched line.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This is the default mode when printing to a tty.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] When **stdout** is not a tty, then ripgrep will default to the standard grep-like format.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] One can force this format in Unix-like environments by piping the output of ripgrep to **cat**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag can be disabled with **--no-heading**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag prints the help output for ripgrep.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Unlike most other flags, the behavior of the short flag, **-h**, and the long flag, **--help**, is different.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] The short flag will show a condensed help output while the long flag will show a verbose help output.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] The verbose help output has complete documentation, where as the condensed help output will show only a single line for every flag.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag controls how ripgrep determines this system's hostname.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] When set, ripgrep will run this executable, with no arguments, and treat its output (with leading and trailing whitespace stripped) as your system's hostname.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] When not set (the default, or the empty string), ripgrep will try to automatically detect your system's hostname.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] On Unix, this corresponds to calling **gethostname**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] ripgrep uses your system's hostname for producing hyperlinks.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Set the format of hyperlinks to use when printing results.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Hyperlinks make certain elements of ripgrep's output, such as file paths, clickable.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This generally only works in terminal emulators that support OSC-8 hyperlinks.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Alternatively, a format string may correspond to one of the following aliases: **default**, **none**, **cursor**, **file**, **grep+**, **kitty**, **macvim**, **textmate**, **vscode**, **vscode-insiders**, **vscodium**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] The alias will be replaced with a format string that is intended to work for the corresponding application.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This is replaced with a path to a matching file.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] The path is guaranteed to be absolute and percent encoded such that it is valid to put into a URI.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Note that a path is guaranteed to start with a /.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This is replaced with your system's hostname.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] was provided, then the hostname returned from the output of that program will be returned.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] If no hostname could be found, then this variable is replaced with the empty string.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] If appropriate, this is replaced with the line number of a match.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] was given), then it is automatically replaced with the value 1.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] If appropriate, this is replaced with the column number of a match.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] corresponds to the value of the equivalent environment variable.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] environment variable is not set, then this is replaced with the empty string.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] An empty format string is equivalent to the **none** alias.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] In this case, hyperlinks will be disabled.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] At present, ripgrep does not enable hyperlinks by default.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] If you aren't sure what format to use, try **default**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Like colors, when ripgrep detects that stdout is not connected to a tty, then hyperlinks are automatically disabled, regardless of the value of this flag.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Users can pass **--color=always** to forcefully emit hyperlinks.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Note that hyperlinks are only written when a path is also in the output and colors are enabled.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] ripgrep works this way because it treats the **--color** flag as a proxy for whether ANSI escape codes should be used at all.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This means that environment variables like **NO_COLOR=1** and **TERM=dumb** not only disable colors, but hyperlinks as well.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Similarly, colors and hyperlinks are disabled when ripgrep is not writing to a tty.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] then hyperlinks will not be emitted since the path given does not appear in the output.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] To make the path appear, and thus also a hyperlink, use the **-H/--with-filename** flag.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] , this causes ripgrep to print the number of matches for each file even if there were zero matches.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This is disabled by default but can be enabled to make ripgrep behave more like grep.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag can be disabled with **--no-include-zero**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] When enabled, ripgrep will always use line buffering.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] That is, whenever a matching line is found, it will be flushed to stdout immediately.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This is the default when ripgrep's stdout is connected to a tty, but otherwise, ripgrep will use block buffering, which is typically faster.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag forces ripgrep to use line buffering even if it would otherwise use block buffering.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This overrides the **--block-buffered** flag.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag can be disabled with **--no-line-buffered**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This is enabled by default when stdout is connected to a tty.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag can be disabled by **-N/--no-line-number**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Line numbers are off by default when stdout is not connected to a tty.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Line numbers can be forcefully turned on by **-n/--line-number**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] When given, ripgrep will omit lines longer than this limit in bytes.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Instead of printing long lines, only the number of matches in that line is printed.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] When this flag is omitted or is set to **0**, then it has no effect.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Prints a preview for lines exceeding the configured max column limit.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] When the **-M/--max-columns** flag is used, ripgrep will by default completely replace any line that is too long with a message indicating that a matching line was removed.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] When this flag is combined with **-M/--max-columns**, a preview of the line (corresponding to the limit size) is shown instead, where the part of the line exceeding the limit is not shown.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] If the **-M/--max-columns** flag is not set, then this has no effect.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag can be disabled with **--no-max-columns-preview**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Print only the matched (non-empty) parts of a matching line, with each such part on a separate output line.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Set the path separator to use when printing file paths.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag is intended for overriding the default when the environment demands it (e.g., cygwin).
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] A path separator is limited to a single byte.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Setting this flag to an empty string reverts it to its default behavior.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] That is, the path separator is automatically chosen based on the environment.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Print both matching and non-matching lines.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Another way to achieve a similar effect is by modifying your pattern to match the empty string.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] For example, if you are searching using **rg** *foo*, then using **rg** **'^|***foo***'** instead will emit every line in every file searched, but only occurrences of *foo* will be highlighted.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag enables the same behavior without needing to modify the pattern.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] An alternative spelling for this flag is **--passthrough**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag is useful when you still want pretty output even if you're piping ripgrep to another program or file.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] If a match is found in a file, then ripgrep will stop searching.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This is useful when ripgrep is used only for its exit code (which will be an error code if no matches are found).
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] When **--files** is used, ripgrep will stop finding files after finding the first file that does not match any ignore rules.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Replaces every match with the text given when printing results.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Neither this flag nor any other ripgrep flag will modify your files.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Capture group indices (e.g., **$***5*) and names (e.g., **$***foo*) are supported in the replacement string.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Capture group indices are numbered based on the position of the opening parenthesis of the group, where the leftmost such group is **$***1*.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] The special **$***0* group corresponds to the entire match.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] The name of a group is formed by taking the longest string of letters, numbers and underscores (i.e.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] For example, **$***1a* will be replaced with the group named *1a*, not the group at index *1*.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] If the group's name contains characters that aren't letters, numbers or underscores, or you want to immediately follow the group with another string, the name should be put inside braces.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] For example, **${***1***}***a* will take the content of the group at index *1* and append *a* to the end of it.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] If an index or name does not refer to a valid capture group, it will be replaced with an empty string.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] In shells such as Bash and zsh, you should wrap the pattern in single quotes instead of double quotes.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Otherwise, capture group indices will be replaced by expanded shell variables which will most likely be empty.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Note that the replacement by default replaces each match, and not the entire line.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] To replace the entire line, you should match the entire line.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag can be used with the **-o/--only-matching** flag.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag enables sorting of results in ascending order.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] The order is determined by sorting files in each directory entry during traversal.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Sort by the last modified time on a file.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Sort by the last accessed time on a file.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] If the chosen (manually or by-default) sorting criteria isn't available on your system (for example, creation time is not available on ext4 file systems), then ripgrep will attempt to detect this, print an error and exit without searching.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] To sort results in reverse or descending order, use the **--sortr** flag.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Note that sorting results currently always forces ripgrep to abandon parallelism and run in a single thread.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag enables sorting of results in descending order.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] when doing a reverse lexicographic sort.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] To sort results in ascending order, use the **--sort** flag.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] When set, all ASCII whitespace at the beginning of each line printed will be removed.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag can be disabled with **--no-trim**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag instructs ripgrep to print results with every match on its own line, including line numbers and column numbers.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] With this option, a line with more than one match will be printed in its entirety more than once.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] For that reason, the total amount of output as a result of this flag can be quadratic in the size of the input.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] For example, if the pattern matches every byte in an input file, then each line will be repeated for every byte matched.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] For this reason, users should only use this flag when there is no other choice.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Editor integrations should prefer some other way of reading results from ripgrep, such as via the **--json** flag.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] One alternative to avoiding exorbitant memory usage is to force ripgrep into single threaded mode with the **-j/--threads** flag.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Note though that this will not impact the total size of the output, just the heap memory that ripgrep will use.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag instructs ripgrep to print the file path for each matching line.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This is the default when more than one file is searched.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] is enabled (the default when printing to a tty), the file path will be shown above clusters of matches from each file; otherwise, the file name will be shown as a prefix for each matched line.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag overrides **-I/--no-filename**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag instructs ripgrep to never print the file path with each matching line.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This is the default when ripgrep is explicitly instructed to search one file or stdin.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag overrides **-H/--with-filename**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag instructs ripgrep to sort search results by file path lexicographically in ascending order.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Note that this currently disables all parallelism and runs search in a single thread.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag overrides **--sort** and **--sortr**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag can be disabled with **--no-sort-files**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag suppresses normal output and shows the number of lines that match the given patterns for each file searched.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Each file containing a match has its path and count printed on each line.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] is enabled and the pattern(s) given can match over multiple lines, this reports the number of lines that match and not the total number of matches.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] If only one file is given to ripgrep, then only the count is printed if there is a match.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] The **-H/--with-filename** flag can be used to force printing the file path in this case.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] If you need a count to be printed regardless of whether there is a match, then use **--include-zero**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Note that it is possible for this flag to have results inconsistent with the output of **-l/--files-with-matches**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Notably, by default, ripgrep tries to avoid searching files with binary data.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] With this flag, ripgrep needs to search the entire content of files, which may include binary data.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] But with **-l/--files-with-matches**, ripgrep can stop as soon as a match is observed, which may come well before any binary data.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] To avoid this inconsistency without disabling binary detection, use the **--binary** flag.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This overrides the **--count-matches** flag.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Note that when **-c/--count** is combined with **-o/--only-matching**, then ripgrep behaves as if **--count-matches** was given.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag suppresses normal output and shows the number of individual matches of the given patterns for each file searched.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Each file containing matches has its path and match count printed on each line.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Note that this reports the total number of individual matches and not the number of lines that match.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Print only the paths with at least one match and suppress match contents.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Note that it is possible for this flag to have results inconsistent with the output of **-c/--count**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] With this flag, ripgrep might stop searching before the binary data is observed.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] But with **-c/--count**, ripgrep has to search the entire contents to determine the match count, which means it might see binary data that causes it to skip searching that file.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This overrides **--files-without-match**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Print the paths that contain zero matches and suppress match contents.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This overrides **-l/--files-with-matches**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Enable printing results in a JSON Lines format.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] A message that indicates a file is being searched and contains at least one match.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] A message the indicates a file is done being searched.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This message also include summary statistics about the search for a particular file.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] A message that indicates a match was found.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This includes the text and offsets of the match.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] A message that indicates a contextual line was found.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This includes the text of the line, along with any match information if the search was inverted.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] The final message emitted by ripgrep that contains summary statistics about the search across all files.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Since file paths or the contents of files are not guaranteed to be valid UTF-8 and JSON itself must be representable by a Unicode encoding, ripgrep will emit all data elements as objects with one of two keys: **text** or **bytes**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] **text** is a normal JSON string when the data is valid UTF-8 while **bytes** is the base64 encoded contents of the data.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] The JSON Lines format is only supported for showing search results.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] It cannot be used with other flags that emit other types of output, such as **--files**, **-l/--files-with-matches**, **--files-without-match**, **-c/--count** or **--count-matches**. ripgrep will report an error if any of the aforementioned flags are used in concert with **--json**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Other flags that control aspects of the standard output such as **-o/--only-matching**, **--heading**, **-r/--replace**, **-M/--max-columns**, etc., have no effect when **--json** is set.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] However, enabling JSON output will always implicitly and unconditionally enable **--stats**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] A more complete description of the JSON format used can be found here: https://docs.rs/grep-printer/*/grep_printer/struct.JSON.html.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag can be disabled with **--no-json**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Please use this when filing a bug report.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] The **--debug** flag is generally useful for figuring out why ripgrep skipped searching a particular file.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] The debug messages should mention all files skipped and why they were skipped.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] To get even more debug output, use the **--trace** flag, which implies **--debug** along with additional trace data.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] When this flag is enabled, all error messages related to parsing ignore files are suppressed.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] By default, error messages are printed to stderr.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] In cases where these errors are expected, this flag can be used to avoid seeing the noise produced by the messages.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag can be disabled with **--ignore-messages**.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] This flag suppresses some error messages.
[src:ripgrep/man-rg-p02] Specifically, messages related to the failed opening and reading of files.
